Street}}Wallace Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me how many years you lived in the house that you were born in?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I know that - we lived there in my - first brother was born there, but before the second one came we had moved into - a new house that had been built, ther
e was - two houses built in what is now Henry Street, and that became Henry Place Easterbrook. Well we got one of these houses and - it was a more - more modern house, the room and kitchen - and the back kitchen. And the - a wash house, a - a modern house
. Well Jim would be born there, and he was born in 1889.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you think you moved because your parents needed more room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Well you see Jim was coming and we - we'd only a room and kitchen where we were and I've no doubt that when Jim was on the way that - that would be the reason that we - that we moved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Where did you move to after that? You moved from the house in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wallace Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 From - into the one which is now {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And - and it started off as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, then there was
 another block of houses - beyond that got built on. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And we moved into number four there, and that was up a stair with another bedroom. That was the - the - the - Tannock built these houses and they were quite more modern, and they - they - and that became {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How long did you stay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Now, we would leave there in 1901.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Where did you go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 To {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. We came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in March 1901.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you've stayed here ever since?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And I've been here all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me how many brothers and sisters you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I was the eldest and there was - two brothers younger - than me, and then - a younger brother of the second marriage and - and he would be born in 1896. He was born in - he was born in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and in 1896.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Have you any idea how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I could find out, it would take a wee bit of - well I can give you that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he belong to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, he - the fourth generation of his. Fourth of his generation anyway.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And he was a plasterer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Slater. Slater, a master slater. Master slater. There was - Thomas and John and John and William, so he was the fourth generation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he ever do any extra work apart from the slaters business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. He'd no - well they were slaters and slate merchants they were. No. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He wouldn't ever be out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Have you any idea how old your mother would be when you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - I daresay I could find - I could get that sorted out. I'll find out.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You said she was a cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, she was cook. Yes, she'd be cook in different places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did she do any work outside the house after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, no - no women did then, oh no, never. There was no women worked out then.; No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She didn't do any work at home either?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, there was no such a thing as doing anything. There - there was at that time, there certainly was people that had to do - take in work you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Washing and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But your mother didn't have to do anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, nothing of that kind. We were rather - well, my father - when he could get the other house and
 - it's difficult to say but we sort of kept ourselves just a wee bit - he didn't amalgamate with the people that he was living amongst, if you can understand. He come of a - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 His family had their own business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Their own business, and - th
ey were friendly enough with people but we just didnae - we werenae just - of them sort -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You lived most of the time when you were small in the house in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, I can remember 
that - well until - this is a wee bit - I - I didn't like to say but, until - after we got the step-mother it was a very happy time. And I can remember - I must have been a winsome kind of kid, you know, I know that because - I must say I was a marry chil
d
 I - I was - I'm only knowing now looking back - that - the houses I could go into in - that you were made welcome. Maybe there was nae other wee kids about, but - I know that we were very happy. I can remember - sitting - well in these days the houses ha
d
 a - a mantelpiece - and a grate - one of these grates with ribs in, a wee oven at the side of the - and a wee fire under the oven and - and father had a - an armchair, you don't see them now, but a - a wooden armchair, sitting up on his knee, and he'd pu
t his knee - his feet up on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 mantel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
-piece. And I would be sitting on his knees like, and looking in his eyes. What do you see? I see a wee lassie. See the - so that - that - and I know I had nice hair, I know that. It wasnae - it wasnae ginger or gold bu
t - very - I had bonny hair, I know that. And - now if - photographs there - 'cos where are the photographs put now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me what size of house the house in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was? How many rooms did it have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, you see there was four in a
 block. And the downstairs houses had only one kitchen and a back kitchen and a wash house did the four. And the upstairs houses had one - one had an extra room that came in over the hallway. Well we got - and we went into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}four Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, it had the - t
he - the extra bedroom. By this time I was needing a - a bedroom. And I suppose it was - but I think the boys got that bedroom and - well, we'd a bed in the - in - there was a bed in the kitchen and a bed in the room and a bed in the wee bedroom. That was
 usual. Everybody had a bed in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't have any rooms like a sitting room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no. But - but - but - but - the - the bed - the - the parlour - it was parlours then, the parlour was for - a round table in it, nice - extra things in 
it, it had a - it was the parlour, and - but the bed was still there. And there was a carpet on the floor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 There wouldn't be a carpet in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh no, what - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 linoleum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . Linoleum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your mother have anybody to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Only occasion. Nobody - nobody in that time to live, anybody had to help. Maybe - maybe get the washerwoman would come in. Some people very - not very many. But a washerwoman in. Well, not very many, I would say a very - no, I don't think that any of 
these people ever got - there might have been stuck, but no, they were - they - they couldnae afford a washerwoman. But there was people - in - better class houses, they - employed - could get a washerwoman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So your mother actually did the washing in the wash house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
She was a very good mother. My - my - well I'm speaking - well I don't know what she was, I was too young to remember - much about her. When I'm speaking now it's my step-mother I'm speaking of. She was a very good step-mother. But no love.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But she would look after you physically?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Very well. Made our clothes, she made clothes. And we were well fed, better fed and better cared for than the people we lived amongst, if you can understand. But she made the best of everything sh
e had. And she had a sewing machine. And - she made them clothes. I can remember when we were kids grandfather used to have - he'd any good clothes he had he sent them to us and we'd unpick them and - we unpicked the clothes and she made trousers for the 
boys and jackets. And - before I would - well - I certainly - in my own mother's time I can remember - getting a dress from Mooney's, 'cos that was the first thing people thought about when there was a death, mournings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Even for wee tots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, I 
had a black dress. I can remember - I go back to my mother's time I can remember Miss Bryson making me the black velvet dress I had. Now, that's when I would be - before I was three. Oh I can remember that quite well, can smell the lining yet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well we wore clogs. Clogs. I think we'd have shoes for Sunday. But we wore clogs to the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your father mend any of the shoes or the clogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, whenever he - whenever he had a - anything needed to be - no - if you nee
d - if your caulker was coming off you'd to go to the clogger and he would put a nail in and he'd put the caulker on for you, and you got a row if you didnae - have the caulker. Oh yes, we - we - you'd to go to Hutcheson, take it away to Hutcheson - go up
 
with it and you sat and waited 'til he - to get the old nail, put a new nail in, I don't know what he'd charge it for but - but - and then if you needed new caulker well you could go and get them on. At the cloggers. Oh yes, you went to the cloggers. I ne
v
er had boots 'til I would be - oh a good big lassie, maybe - oh - ten or eleven or - maybe ten before I got a pair of boots and I didn't like them, they were very strong boots. Heel plates, other - although the other girls had boots but mine had heel plat
e
s. And they were they were that kind of hard leather. But you see - many of the other girls that had boots were - maybe they were - might have been in better - in some things - we were well-fed, the dress didn't matter so much to them. Maybe - there might
 
have been other girls at the school with us that were father might have had more wages, you see. Oh there - there was no doubt there was other girls at the school that - they were - better dressed as we - as what I was. Because, as I say, my father and mo
t
her had to work with what they had to work with. And every week the rent and tax money was put past. Every week. That was - my father said that was the - they did - what they did from the very earliest days. He told me - well I was going to - I was going 
t
o lend money to somebody. And he said, now - lend - never lend money to anybody. If you've got money give it away. Never lend it. If you want to - to give 'em - give them it, well - you'd lend it quicker than you'd give it. And he said, now never lend it,
 
he says, that was the only - time your mother and I ever fell out. The widow down the stairs - was behind the rent and she wanted the loan of a pound. And of course your mother wondered if then could give it she'd ask him, my daddy. He says - he said, oh 
no, he said, can't do that. He said, if you've a pound to spare you can give her it. But never lend it.; So she wasna pleased, well she wouldna think - well - she would lend it -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She wanted to do her neighbour a good turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. But he wouldna ag
ree with it, he said that was the only time they ever }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 quarrelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
, that was over the lending of the pound to this person down the stair, that could never have returned it. Because she'd a big family. That family down - that lived in that Wallace Street hous
e down below us - and there was only the room and kitchen, and the Millers. There was - well there was Janet and Grace, whether they were - in the house at that time, but there was Janet and Grace was the eldest. And there was Sam, Mary, Libbie, Walter, W
illie and Tony. All in the room and kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Eight people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well that's - that's - but - but whether Janet - and grace - I don't think they'd be married. But they were - there were - there were Janet and Grace. But - the - the rest were all there.
 And the - the - as I say they'd only a room and kitchen. The mother was a wee bit canny. I nice body but canny. And - the father was a - a goods guard on the railway. And - but I think they were - they were both kinda canny. And Sam - Sam was - was maybe
 bit canny. Same was a very - Janet and Grace and as I say Sam - Janet, Grace and Sam - Sam and Mary, Mary was no quite right. There was just something about them all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Something lacking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. But they could all look after theirselves. And - Sam g
ot a job in the mill - of course he was - he was a fairly - old, and - he was - very sad story, he came - and at this time mill paid off, Sam came home crying, what was he going to do. What am I going to do? How shall we pay the rent, what are we going to
 do, how will we pay the rent? When he was laid off work. Of course everybody knew Sam Miller, latter days. For you see he'd tell tall stories and - he was just always -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Not quite in this world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your father help - your mother with an
y of the jobs around the house, doing fires and cleaning or cooking?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
My father was a very good father every way. Yes. He was a good father. After my mother - my own mother died - he got a housekeeper but he sat in the room and he told me he'd made me - tried to make me wee draws. He was a good father in every way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did his best for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would he decorate the house himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well these days - I don't know - oh he could - he could paint but what the - the decorations were - 
they were never as elaborate as what they are now. I don't remember much about that. Further - that - I remember him telling me that - when the mother took her trouble, 'cos she had this trouble and she had gone to Moniaive and she'd taken us children wit
h her, well - of course - well she wouldna be - properly - doctors in these days didnae - well hadna the skill like what they've got now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did your father look after you himself quite a bit, to the extent of giving you a bath and dressing you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh 
well, there was - you see, we got a housekeeper. And she was a very good housekeeper. She was a very good housekeeper. But - he - he would sit in the room of course. She - he'd been - brought up here and they would have a maid here that - he wouldnae sit 
w
ith the housekeeper in the kitchen. He would sit in the room. The first kitchen. But she was quite a good housekeeper. And I can remember that - well I were going out walk with somebody with a pram that I remember, it must have been the housekeeper. 'Cos 
I remember going up the Marken Road well, we just went a walk with the pram. And meeting the wild }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 houses now}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  it'd be the - Drichton or Ellengowan carriage pair coming down but they reared and to me that was always the road with the wild horses. And they'd r
ear at something. I remember the wild horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your father ever tell you stories? You said you sat on his knee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I must have been pretty wee then when I sat on his knee. But I can remember going to church with my father. Now that would 
be after my mother would - die. And sitting with him and him holding my hand - in the church, quite well. And I had a - I had a hat - round hat with ribbons down the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . I would be in mournings you know. Possibly wear a black hat. But - my father was - v
ery dead on us doing what was right. And he was a great singer, he was a good singer, my father. And he was always singing in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he get everybody to join in with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, no, he sang himself. Anybody would - but he was - he was very 
fond of singing. And - now - he - we - we would belong to St Michaels church, and he had taken an active interest in the church at that time, you know, he was - there was a temperance society and he had something to do with the temperance society and sing
ing and - he certainly had taken an interest in things at St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 Michaels}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  church. Of course I've no doubt my mother had to do with that too. She was a good - she'd be a good influence, I know that. And - I remember the first song I ever - remember hi}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  singing w
as the Queen - Last Next to the Queen had three Mary's. That was about the first thing I - Last night the Queen had three Mary's. Mary Beaton and Mary Seaton and Mary Carmicheal and me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he ever take you out anywhere else apart from the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh we always went walks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You walked a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. All - all families did these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Sunday afternoons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, that's the done thing. You went to church, we - went regularly to church. Regularly to church every Sunday. In the morni
ngs. And - and afternoon, after dinner we would go to church - go for a walk. Went for a walk. Various places, if we - if we - it was a good Sunday we would go - decide we would go walk to Dock Foot today. And that was the Dock Foot, that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That's what's Dock Park nowadays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
The Dock Foot was where the - the ships come in. The ships come in at the Dock Foot. The Dock Foot. The Dock was - the - go to the park further up. The Dock. And we - we would go to the Dock Foot, another time we would may
be go around the - the New Quay, as far as the New Quay and back up Kingholm Road and back Castledykes. And - Eastfield, we didna like going to Eastfield because that was a very short walk, we just go to East - through Eastfield today. Well we called it t
he horses broth. Well we got to horses broth -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Why was it called that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
The horses broth was - Crawford was a - bred horses. Kept horses and bred horses and I've no doubt he would boil - beans for the horses. You see, they boil stuff now, beans - 
boil them, there was a smell of broth. And of course it was the - the mash, the mash being boiled for the horses and we used to - go down to the horses broth, which was - up - Alderman Hill, and over the hill and down into Eastfield and by the horses brot
h. And - and along - what is now Leafield Road, and up - and up home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have any wee jobs to do in the house when you were small?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When I got the step - step-mother, that was another thing. Other kids di
dna get it to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She made you work did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - well we were sent down the stair to clean my father's boots every morning before ever - before he started work early, maybe six o'clock. If you - if it was the dark mornings well he was up to -
 a place to see his father. 'Cos his father lived alone. But - my father's boots and he - he would - come in at eight o'clock and you'd to clean father's boots and have them - cleaned for his breakfast, and he went away again at nine. And we had our own c
l
ogs to clean every morning, we did them down at the back door. And had an occasional fight about who's got the brush, well I'm waiting on the brush, I'm waiting on the black brush. And - then we'd - ash bucket to put out. And - when it was our turn for th
e stair well - stair to sweep down, it was our turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Everybody in the block would have to take a turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. And all these but - and then I - washed the breakfast dishes or helped. As I got older I peeled the potatoes before I went to school, there were too many jobs. A result I was always late for the school. And I didna like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your brothers have jobs to do as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh they - they had their boots to clean too. They had their own boots to clean. But the boys - the boys didna get - no, no, I don't think the boys had any jobs. Not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You got the heavy end of the stick being the oldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I - being a girl. Being a girl. Of course, I could realize - I remember - it's if a - it's - it's - it's - vexing to repeat these things bu
t I can remember - this happened in the house in Henry Place before we moved to number four. And possibly - it might have been the first Christmas that we ever - we always hung up our stockings. But this Christmas after we got the new mother - John - I'd 
b
een asleep, John hadna been sleeping, or he woke - he woke up and he woke me. And he says, Santa Claus has been here. And he got a trumpet from - from his stocking. I got a book - Child's Own Magazine, and it would be a - a - an annual, a shilling thing. 
A
nd - and Joun had blown the trumpet, and - of course that fetched my mother through. And we got a row for no sleeping. We got a row and I - I don't know what happened, but - I certainly - was nae worse then - but I would - I was supposed to have told a li
e. What - the lie was I don't know. But I got a row.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She was quite strict then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - she was very strict. And as I say there was no love. Whether it was jealousy I don't know. But - but - next morning, Christmas morning - I got a clout and - and
 I got a battering. And - and I can - oh well - my father says, now that will do Mary. That will do. Christmas morning. A wee kid. Well - she used to read us stories out of that - Childrens magazine. And I listened. And there was a - a story about a - thi
s
 girl, it was a continued story. And she'd been away with a - the gipsies had got her in the caravan, used to think, well - that lassie was awful well for going away with the gypsies. Yes. No. Of course she had been kind of - she'd been brought up on a fa
rm and - farms in these days it was the boys that worked. Not the girls. The girls had to work to let the boys get - do something. Let them train for something. I quite see how it - she'd been brought up in that strict -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 In a different way from the town people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, it was - it was the - well only for the money. As long as the boys got - the girls had to bring in their wages and they handed their wages over to the mother. And the mother kept the purse, and as long as the boys could get - and her 
brother, she'd had two brothers - the one became a - now one - must have served his time to the trade, he'd been in London and Edinburgh and Liverpool and - but - it was just the way they'd been brought up. And - we never got - there was poorer kids that 
we - we played amongst had more money to spend than we had. We never got money like - but then we were always - well put on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would probably be better fed than them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Better - better fed and better cared for in every way. And - trained - better trained. But - the people - I know that the neighbours knew that we were - pretty harshly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 eat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
What about your wee brothers when you were small, did you have to help to dress them and keep an eye on them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh there was only - see by this ti
me - now by - '96 I had to go off the school. She was very ill when that baby - baby was born '96. She was very ill. And - I would be eleven years old then and I was off the school - for a few weeks, having to - to help in the house. Having to - to - to -
 to - do in the house. And - I missed a wee bit but - I think that they seemed to understand at the school. There was nothing said. I don't think it would be difficult to pick up - in some ways what I had missed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. And your clothes had all to be folded and put on the chair and your hair brushed. Your hair - remember your hair - it was rolled up, brushed and - your - pair plaited and - oh yes, certainly - you got out to play but - if you weren
't there at the time, well - well I didna get much out to play. The boys used to get out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your step-mother put you to bed or did you have to go yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well we were put - no, when we were little, oh yes, we were sent to bed ourselves of a night. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had a bedroom to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Latterly. As I - as I got older, I would he maybe - now - well, I - I could sort out but I - certainly as I got older, John and I slept together in a bed and then - when we got into this - this number 
four, I got a bed to myself. But the two boys slept in the - before 19 - 1896, before that time - I had my own bed and the two boys, they were in the wee bedroom. And then the young boy came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your step-mother make a big difference between you chil
dren and her own son?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - he was very little when she died. But we - oh he was an awfully nice boy and of course we liked the wee boy, we - oh we were - very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You were very fond of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. He was an - he was an awful nice boy
. And a bonny boy. When he was - well - he - he died -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about a bathroom in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - well we bathed in front of the kitchen fire every Saturday night. The tub was brought up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was it a big tin one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, a - a - a tub, a tu
b. A tub with hoops on it, a wash tub, the wash tube was brought up from the wash house every Saturday night, kettle and a pot of water was put on the side of the fire and you were bathed every Saturday night. My hair was washed every Saturday night. As I
 say I had nice hair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get a change of clothes after you'd had your bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, oh yes, you got clean clothes, we were - as I say, we were well looked after. We'd clean clothes and - and - bathed and put to bed, that was Saturday night. 
I - on the Saturday night there was a - Mr Kenyon used to come round with - he was a Methodist and he used to often come round with - tracts on Saturday night, with these tracts, stories and these. And - that was - Sunday mornings, well - for our breakfas
t on a Sunday morning, well - sausages used to be bought at Liptons as a special treat. And - it maybe sausage and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 potatoes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  scones as our Sunday morning breakfast. But at other breakfasts we'd always porridge and milk. Porridge and milk every morning. Every morning of life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get anything else for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get bread and butter or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, bread and butter, possibly a wee bit of bacon. I can't remember very much but we - or might have had an egg, we would pos
sibly get an egg, but we'd porridge - porridge and - bread and butter or scone or something after porridge every morning. And - and - the milkman - now could I bring in the milkman here? Well you see the milk came round - milk came round - the milkcart ca
m
e round every morning and it was from Netherwood. Andrew Howat came round - now I think he would - he would - come in about - might have been about eight o'clock, and - everybody liked Andrew, and blew his whistle and you - down you go for your milk. Now 
-
 well I think it could be in a measure. Now I think - a half pint wouldna be much use, that I think you would get a pint. And then you got skimmed milk for your porridge. That was skimmed milk was where he carried both sweet milk and - and the skimmed mil
k
 was where they had taken the milk - the cream off for the butter. Well that was the skimmed milk. In the summer time, well it's sometimes wet. My father would say, that's milk wented. Well there never was a lot gone. But as soon as he said that the milk 
was wented, he could take it, never seemed any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That means sour does it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - turned. He would say, that milk's wented this morning. And as soon as he say that there was milk over. As soon as he say that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It put you off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would. O
h no. I would sup my porridge dry, work my jaws to get away to get my plate, 'cos he'd always take away your - dirty plate and - the milk would go down the drain. I couldn't do with sour milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you all have breakfast together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Your father would get his with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he have anything before he went out first thing in the morning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No, no, no. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He just came back at eight o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 For his breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about at dinner time, what did you have at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well our food at these days - I couldn't say but - well, I - when we were little - half a pound of steak as stew, meat in these days was very cheap. I would think - I don't know - we would get boiling beef - boiling beef would be goo
d. And - soup meat. Potato soup was made - potato soup would be made with - with - a bit of meat of some kind. Sh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 ee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 ps head - often had a sheeps head and that was made into soup - broth, she}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 ps head broth. And we got the sheeps to eat, 'cos the tongue was a
 good bit of meat in, in the sheeps head. And I think you got a sheeps head for fivepence. Then - my mother - I could remember going for a pluck. Now do you know what a pluck is? A pluck's - the plucks the throat - and the liver and the lights, that bit. 
This bit see up here. The liver, lights and heart. Well you get that - the - the throat is taken out and - and - the liver and the lights and the heart, and you could get that for sevenpence, the whole thing. For sevenpence. A sheeps pluck.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That should feed a family for a couple of days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well she - well they could make haggis with that, she made haggis. She could make the haggis. But I've been sent - that's what I remember being sent for a sheeps pluck and it was sevenpence. Now - it's nearly - it
's at least six shillings a pound for the liver, sheeps liver. If it's no more, I just couldn't exactly tell you what they charge for it. And when she made haggis with - that, well - that lasted a while, and boiled it, and you had to get the - you'd to ge
t the - now the sheep - sheep barley - you got the sheep barley. You see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That was to put the haggis in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
To put the haggis you see, well you see you'd to order to that, because - you see when they take - they usually take it out of the beast, yo
u see, they just cut the - the haggis is the stomach. They just slit it, the bulk of it and this - the contents come out. But if it's to be for a haggis, cut for the haggis they must keep that whole. Empty it - they must empty it from the top you see. You
 see, otherwise - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Or else it wouldn't be all in one piece for the haggis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get pudding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Rice pudding. Rice pudding. Cornflower was a great go then. Curds. I never liked curds. No, curds and whey. I never liked th
e curds and whey. But rice pudding, we often had rice pudding, rice with currants in it. Made in a pot. Made in a pot. Of course there was nae gas cookers then, it was all kitchen - made in a kitchen fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was it like a range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, it was a wee -
 it was - you see - you need to see these - what - what these - there was the ribs, and there was a wee hole here and this hole would be bigger. It was a wee oven. A wee oven with a wee fire underneath, kindle - put a wee fire underneath this oven and you
 could bake in it. But - you'd need to be a good baker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would be very difficult to regulate the heat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh it was very difficult. And - but - you could - work with your pans of course you're - iron pans then were good. And once they were - and y
ou could work your fire that - you could set your pans round and - and keep them still cooking, you'd - you'd to learn how to - to work your fire. To build it so - so that it would - wouldna burn away quickly. It's surprising how - how they managed.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have to learn to cook too? Or did your mother do most of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well - I would see her cooking but I - I'd learn when she - when I would be - in my fifteenth year when she died, because I'd learnt to do things. I often think, well - I was tr
ying to make a clootie dumpling in the oven, I've done them many a time. I don't know why I did them but - we always had a dumpling. That was a suet - just a suet dumpling boiled in a pot, in a cloth and tied up and - and we'd get that with syrup. Sometim
es currants in it, I've made that and yet - maybe a month or two I thought I'll make it. It was nae success. And yet - I made them when I was a kid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have a meal at night, did you have a tea at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 We would have our tea maybe about five
 o'clock. And a piece at bedtime. Just a piece. Get a - we would get a syrup piece or - quite a common things was - of course you made your own jam. We never had bought jam. Maybe bought marmalade but - we'd always syrup, we could get a syrupy piece or - 
but I don't think we - we never had margarine, I don't think there was margarine then, there might have been I never mind hearing about margarine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It was all butter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, we used butter. And you often got a sugary piece. You know, butter with a wee bit of sugar. Sugary piece. It was quite a good thing, a sugary piece. Oh well, sugary piece. And - oh she baked scones, she baked scones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had a proper tea with bread and scones and cakes and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh scones. Bread, scone. No cakes, n
ever cakes. No, no. Oh I remember - we used to have a certain message, go down to the bakers window and you stand and look in, if I was sent for six cakes - I would have that one, and that one. I would choose the six, if I - if I was sent for }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  cakes wha
t cakes I would choose. And if I was sent for twelve what a difficulty, I had to find twelve different cakes. This was what you looked at the window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did you get anything special on Sundays, you said you got sausages for your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - w
ell the - potato - very often potato scones for a - fried potato scones on a Sunday morning. And - well Liptons - it'd be pork sausages from Liptons and - potato scones, and - well - on a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about Sunday dinnertime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Sunday dinnertime, we'd a
lways - a good dinner. Now you could - oh you see they're getting a shillingsworth of pork, now that would be a pound and a half of pork. And she could roast that in front of the fire - in what they called the dutch oven. And it clipped onto the ribs. The
 dutch oven clipped onto the ribs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Just a sort of box thing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I'll let you - you ken what flank of mutton's like? Well, flank of beef, you imagine it in beef would be much bigger and that - the think bit of the flank down towards - w
ell - in the front's to a point. Well - up here in beef it's much thicker. thick. You see. And a pound of - of - a bit of that thick bit would be cut and it was right good and it'd be roasted in the pot and - and it was aside the fire for - for Sunday tea
 
sometimes. We'd have that and bread. And - although it was nice, it made a good meal that, and it's really a nice bit of meat that. Yes, but it's - but - it's - it's no - it's - no - I'll no buy that now. You see - you see there's - you only got a wee bit
 
of rib at the - it was - used to be put in the windows, wee chunks, and there was just a wee of bit of the - of the rib - left where it had - where it had - had been cut you see. But they would - they would - they'd look at that - oh - I wouldn't take it 
now, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have to eat all your fat when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You were never allowed to lose the fat, always - you eat if you couldn't - get it away in your pocket well and good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you'd go that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Pj we--
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well - sometime
s there maybe a good bit of fat. But I can eat fat now and the fat's nothing but a bother to me to eat. Of course I shouldna eat it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So your mother made scones and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did she ever make her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Bread. No,
 no, she never did. I've a feeling she may have tried it, no, no. She may - I think I've gone for yeast, maybe somebody other has tried - no, she'd - I think she did, but no - not - not - no, I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Not regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. But she certainly made good sc
ones and tarts. Make her own tart. And my - we had an allotment, my father - he - had this allotment, we - grew his own potatoes and rhubarb and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your mother bottle any of the fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 There was no bottling then. No, no. Oh we never had
 fruit, we'd only potatoes and rhubarb, cabbage and - and these sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did she ever make any pickles or wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, she made pickles. She - because we'd cauliflower and she pickled cauliflowers. Oh yes, you see when it - cauliflowers they come all of a sudden, all at once and she used to pickle them, my father liked pickles and she would pickle the cauliflowers.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about making wine or beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Oh my father made - botanic beer and - he used to make this botanic beer and bottle
 it and - and he - he got botanic - what is it he got - Newhall and Mason's, a wee bottle of stuff for making this botanic beer. He sent away for it. Or he'd get it possibly at the chemists, and they made this botanic beer and it - it - it was gallon bott
les and it was wired down and - and then - through the night sometimes these burst, they used to burst open. Oh it was right good stuff, the botanic beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get to taste it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh we all got it, we got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Everybody got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. It
 was good. He - he was a teetotaler. My father was teetotaler. You see botanic beer was - was teetotal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It wasn't alcoholic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no. Oh no. Of course there was shops you could buy that stuff in. Any amount of - well there's wee shops that sold t
reacle beer too, you could make the treacle, beer, I've made treacle beer. And, you get so much treacle and water and a wee bit of yeast or something. I've made that, but - I'll no say it's very successful but - oh you could - and you could get a bottle o
f botanic beer for - well the shops - wee shops used to sell it penny or tuppence or something. They had a - they were - big bottle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about tins of food in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Tinned salmon was - only remember - salmon and they were tall tins you kno
w, I don't know what they were but - and it wasnae dear. But I think - I can only remember salmon, getting tin of salmon. I think that was quite - quite - quite poor could buy a tin of salmon, it wasnae very dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You don't remember your mother using any tins of meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, no, no, oh no, oh no, no, no, no such a thing as tins of stuff. Not such a thing. Vegetables were very cheap. Carrots, turnips were - they were very reasonable, because people handa the money, there was wasna a lot of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Were you allowed to talk when you were having a meal? Or did you have to sit quiet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
We were very well brought up that way. In fact we were never to talk very much at all. We were brought up the children - that children should be seen and not heard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
If the salt was at the other end of the table and you wanted some could ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well - I never ever remember asking for salt. Everything was seasoned. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you choose what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. You did not. You ate what yo
u were given and you were thankful to get it, and if it was something extra good you licked the plate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh if there was dumpling or that kind of thing you - you never - you were never hungry. Potatoes you'd get as much
 as you wanted. Oh you never - never - stinted with anything to eat. And we - there was nae money for - for buying fancy things. She baked maybe treacle loaf or something of that kind but - there was - there was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804 nae }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 money. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you think she would 
ever have to go short so that you children and your father could have enough food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Not in these days. Latterly - the latter days when she wasna well - I could remember her - her having been down to her last penny one time, well she maybe need ext
ras. But I could remember she was very - well she had need - needed - I could remember that - she never did buy extra anythings for herself, and I could remember that she hadnae got the money. But it was never - there was never no debt. Never. You never s
aid for - mark it down. Never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She seems to have been very conscientious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. Oh no there was never such a thing as - never in our lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No credit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When you were at the table did you have to hold your knife and for
k a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
We just had a - we just had a fork. We just had a fork, we were gae big before we ever needed a knife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Could you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 bring}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  any toys or books to the table with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well we'd very few toys. Very very few toys. I could - I'd onl
y one doll. My father had made it when I was a wee lassie, it was a wooden doll, it was made out of wood, it was Jean, and - a - a friend - that when - as I say I must have been a likeable youngster because this - girl, she worked in the mill and she boug
h
t me this doll and she dressed it. And I got this doll, but - the doll would be a wax doll and possibly only cost sixpence undressed. I knew where she bought it. And she had it all dressed, but - I had to take care of the doll so it was put past. Can I ha
ve my doll out to play with? On a Sunday, could I get me doll. Well I'd get the doll out on a Sunday. With the result that I got too big for the doll and it was given to the child down the - stair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you never had very much fun with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Kid 
down the stair would - would - she would have the pleasure of the doll.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
When you were sitting at the table and you all sat together, did you all sit in the same seats at every meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Your own seat, the - the table was at the window, my father sat
 at the head and mother we all sat round the table.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about when your brothers were younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
And my father - my father say the grace if we were all at the table. He did say grace. Maybe - not always, but I know my father did say grace if we were having a meal together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
What about when you finished, did you have to say anything before you left the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no - oh no, no, no, I can't remember saying, can I leave the table?, You just left the table. That would be - be - get ready for the school. No. When I came home from the school I'd always the knives to clean. When I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 On a sander thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
On a - on a knife board. I had to clean the knives at night. They were steel knives and you'd - the knives to clean and maybe coals to bring in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did you find your stepmother an easy person to talk to or was she not the sort of person you could tell your troubles too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, we didn't talk very much. We - as I say there was - that - that - it wasnae - when I see - children now and
 I see - that - my younger son's wife and her kids, they're all - they were - no, she wasna any sort of person to talk to. Because - I don't know - not - no, I could knit stockings, mother can I go out to play? Yes, take your stocking with you. Yes. Well 
- take your - take your stocking with you. Now I was supposed to take your stocking and knit.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And play at the same time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Now what happened, you planked the stuff down and about five minutes before you go - went in you would sit and do the knitting and you pulled a - pulled a stitch. Take your stocking with you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you find you could speak to your father more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you see - my father would do the speaking, no - no I never minded speaking to my father. Fact - I got estranged from my father. Estranged.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 After he got married again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well of - of course he - yes, he got estranged.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You were always brought up to respect them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. And - when I was in - at the school - I daresay I told you this before well - I - I was
 quite a bright child at school I know that. And - did I need to tell you that bit before about the school books and that? Did I tell you about ... oh well when I went to - I can remember - now - we would have the housekeeper who went to the school. I wou
l
d be five years old then. We would have the housekeeper then. And I can remember her going the first day to school and the girl that took me remembered seeing the - she's dead now, and she did never remember taking me to school but I remember going with h
e
r and coming back with this line for my father to fill, this is my name and - and all my particulars. Had to take this line back to the school. And where in I sat in the school beside the piano and - the book they got is the penny book. Now the penny book
,
 I think it would be made with the - it had blackbirds - a wee book about that - that - it was blackbirds on the outside, it was a brown cover and a - and a black square, and blackbirds on it. And then the ABC's were all in it and MLO's and that, and the 
f
irst lesson, and of course the teacher put up O, she didn't - you'd to learn the ABC's and the ITH LOS OO and all these things. They went on midday. And then - the first picture in that book was a cat. A cat. A cat. A cat sat on a mat and all this sort of
 thing you know, rat. Wasna a - a - next book was a threepenny book. Now, it was a - a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had to pay for the books did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. A threepenny book, and - I wasnae long on the threepenny book, and I could remember it had a blue cover. Hop, hop
, hop, off to the shop to buy some nice new toys. And there was something about the drum, or what you could buy from the - and I was just thinking - now it was a Miss McAlistair that was in that, but not the McAlistairs that - that - came on in late years
 
but a Miss McAlistair taught that. And then I shifted into the fourpenny. And then - first standard after that. Now I would be seven in the first standard, that was - that was the first standard. And - you got the - you had a slate. We'd always had a slat
e
 - and then - they came to the - well, of course you asked questions and - you'd answer. And the first - standard - we'd try for the promise - the need for coming for trying for the prize you see. Considered who used to get the prize, well - so any of the
 
- of the - better - who the teacher thought - so many of us dropped a book out onto the floor, we may have had questions asked before that but we were - had to drop the book on the floor and - you do this sums or whatever it was we got on the floor. And -
 that was to try for the prize. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 Prize day}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 came round, I got the McLellan prize, which was the - a half crown. Now the McLellan prize I think's still going on in schools. Somebody would have left that money. I think it'll be in St Micheals and Loreburn. But 
I think there's still a McLellan prize, however it's given I don't know. But they'll have been given money and it was the interest of this money. McLellan's money - that - that - I think - two and six would be the first - second and the first had two and 
s
ix. The fifth and sixth got five shillings. Yes, for - that was the McLellan prize which was supposed to.be. I had got also at one period even before that or after it, the Bible prize. A - a book for Bible. And - the Bible, we got to learn the Bible at th
e
 school, and I think it was a good thing. All through the school you got - Bible knowledge. We were taught Bible in school. And - now I got the McLellan prize, well - that was the - the half crown, I don't know what came of the half crown. But - and then 
they went into the second standard and we got we got - writing with a pen. In a copy book.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What were the teachers like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well my first teacher was a Miss Sehddon, she was infant mistress. I should have said - about Henry school - Hendry would be 
it's first - the first headmaster in that school. He was the first headmaster. He conducted a school under - what is the Southlea church now, - it was named the Territorial Kirk - the Territorial church, and there was a hall underneath and he conducted th
e
 school there but it wasnae a - it wasn't - a - a - a - the - it'd be the Territorial school, and he was the head - he was the master of the Territorial school. Then this - Education Act came into force. This is when the Education Act come into force, and
 
- possibly St Micheals would be built - would be built for this Act coming in. And - he got - the headmastership in St Micheals school from the Territorial school. I can give you date - you can get dates for that. Oh well, well - he - but he came from Ter
r
itorial school and he was in the school through my time and right on 'til - I just forget when he would retire. But - he was a clever wee man. Terrible fond of singing - singing, singing lessons. And - his second in command was Mr Duncan, I think he belon
g
ed to Perthshire. He was a great teacher, that was when - the - as I tell you they put in the extra football ground. He was great with football for boys. And he - but he was - whether he had a degree I don't know but he was a fine - you could learn from M
r
 Duncan far better than you could from Mr Hendry, he could - he could impart the knowledge, if you can understand. He - he - he could - he - yes, he - he liked - he was - but he was awful severe. Oh he could bring the belt down. You - you - you were frigh
tened for him but yet - he was fair. Mr Hendry had his favourites, Mr Duncan had no favourites. And - Mr Hendry - liked the folks, the lassies or boys that could - had his favourites.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he get the ones who were clever to be his favourites?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - in a way -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Or was it ones from better families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - the favourites was - they were - they were - nice enough girls, but Mr Duncan made no difference, but Mr Hendry, he could tell - you could sense the difference. Oh teacher's pet, you see,
 teacher's pet. And - you were quite - quite pleased if the teacher's pet got the belt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did the girls get the belt too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, if they needed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What sort of things did you get the belt for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - well I - I remember only that - I rem
ember getting the belt was - well I was often late, I had work to do, and I was generally running round at the last minute and I was often late. And I had to come through this teacher's room to get to - to our own room. I got the belt coming through there
. I would have come through several times that no I got the belt from him - for coming in late. For I had to go through that room into - into - into - our room you see. I never remember getting much of the belt from teacher. No. But I remember that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 If you did bad work did you get the belt for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh I think that - that - yes, some of them would - would - there were - I can't remember but - oh they - they got the belt if they didnae do it right or if they were caught talking or if they were doi
ng things wrong. They got the belt, oh yes, they - they had to do it - they had to - they had to - be obedient and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You started school when you were five, did you go in the afternoons as well as the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 All day now, all day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It wouldn't take you very long to get to the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Just round the corner, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you would come home for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. And we were very well attended, we got lots of prize for perfect attendance, we were - I think we - we - we kept w
ell, but we were never kept off the school. We were - we were never ill enough to be off the school, I - I never remember being off the school for being ill. But - we'd lots of prizes for perfect attendance, needless to say when we got these two prizes wa
s
 the - the McLellan prize in the first standard and the Bible prize, I don't know whether I got it before that or after. But I can remember the stories in that. And - eeh - I can remember now - being sent - well they used to play golf in the Kingholm. Kno
w where the Kingholm is? Used to play - there was a golf course there. And there was a wee boy playing in the Kingholm, and they're playing, and he was killed with a golf ball. On the Kingholm. He was killed on the Kingholm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He must have been hit on the head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, he was hit on the head. And - Miss Lockerby sent me a message and I saw that wee boy's funeral - in the St Micheals churchyard and I know where the stone is now because I used to visit that and - that grave and he was - he had been a choirboy in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St John's{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I think - I think it was - it was David MacKay, but I know where he's buried. And - he was a choirboy at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St John's{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And this Miss Lockerby asked me - her brother would be - work in - a chemist which is the corner - Lightbodies now, what
ever it is, it used to be - at one time it had been Poole's Corner, Sutherland's Corner, Dover's Corner, I dinna Ken - Fraser's Corner, but aye a chemist there, and - her brother - and she said did I know where Sutherland the chemists was, and I said, yes
.
 Well I would be about - I would say I would be eight then. And she sent me this message to go and of course - I would come - I'd be - it'd be after two o'clock, and when I came to St Michaels here the funeral was - and the choirboys were all there with t
heir surplices on and - the - Mr Denholm was the Vicar. Was - he was - he was the - he wasna the Vicar, he - but he was the - the - well he would be the Vicar but maybe had another name. But he was - he was the head at - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then. And - and I can remem
ber the - the - funeral drawing up and the - the boys all singing this - that went with the - but of course the choir in the church, and singing - through the night of doubt and sorrow, onward goes - they've taken this wee boy and they buried him. Many a 
t
ime we go - we used to visit that - Sunday school time go up to see wee boy's grave. Well - on - a few years ago - I took the whole family and a friend to see it. But I couldna find it. However, I went another day by myself. And the - grass had grown long
 
and the stone had got knocked over, and the grass had grown up over it, you see, that's the time I couldna find it. So this time I went, and I looked and I looked and then I sort of - I knew that was the place. However by the time - the grass around about
 had been cut and then here was the stone, it had - was embedded in the - so - I'd like it if some man would just - cement the wee st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 
one up again. It was a wee corse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would that be a big funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No, in these days without - well, there'd be 
a lot of folk watching. You see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They'd just wait at the side of the road while the hearse went past?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well, the boys robed in the house at the kirk steps which is away now, that house - there was a house at the kirk steps, and that house is 
away. But that would be about here - the - the thing would be there. And the boys would be robbing in this house so they came out and they carried the coffin up and - up there and - that - that was what - that was what I saw in that day, and that was - of
 
course I - we knew about the boy being killed at - with the - with the - the golf ball. Now there's no many folk'll know that, but it was held there. And the man that - the ball was - he was organist in St Michaels church. He was the organist there. So I 
expect that would end - that would put an end to - to the - golf on the Kingholm. 'Course - played - the children played in the Kingholm, you see. But he'd - he'd got the golf ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 At the school did the teachers lay special stress on things like being
 punctual and good manners and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You were well - trained in everything at the school. I think so, you never - you - you - you - you paid attention and did everything, you never spoke back, you never - you - you never spoke unless yo
u were spoken to. Answer - answer questions, I can remember - now there cards in the wall, now this card, it had on it a - a comb - and - some - what - turned out to be hair, and - the things - all the things that you get from a cow you see. And you'd ans
w
er the questions. Well, the - the horn, the cow's horn, there was the cow's horn made the - the - combs and the feet made glue. And what - and then there was this - a cow's hair, I can remember, and - and what would they - what did they use that hair for?
 
And I said, well I'd seen my father using this hair, mixing it to the lime for to hold the lime together. I'd seen my father - taking a - a hair and - separate it and then he'd put it - if he was make - making up lime he threw it in the lime, and that hel
d
 the lime together, the hair you see. And I said, mixing in the lime. So of course I suppose I would - I would be the only kid that would - at that time would have known, of course if I hadna seen my father doing that, but that was the kind of thing that 
w
as hung up, what got from a - a cow. There'd be other animals the same way. And I think - I would think that all teachers would do a certain amount of singing. They would bring a modulator. I don't think you went anywhere, your teacher did it, he taught d
oh ray me's on the modulator. Have they still got modulators? Aye well still got the modulator out and - and - there was a period for singing. Now I think Monday and Wednesday - they were Bible days. Now -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did the minister come in to give you Bible lessons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, the teacher did - the teacher did it. But there was a Bible examination, the - the ministers came in and took the Bible examination. The teacher took the Bible, and there were - I must say that - the knowledge I got in the school has remai
ned with me. And was good for you. And - opening a - I don't know but I think every morning, I don't know whether we - opened a prayer every morning or not, I just kind of forget that. But - I think - in - in the senior part, I think we did sing - Oh God 
o
f Bethlehem and and I think we said the Lord's Prayer. See there was no hall, the door - the sliding doors opened up and the whole - the ministers desk was about the - where he could - they could all hear what he said. The doors were all opened up and you
 
could hear what was going in. And you marched in - you marched in lines, with your lines outside, and somebody - there was always somebody allowed to play the piano and you were - into your lines every morning. I'm no sure whether - whether we did that ev
e
ry day or not. Forgotten that, but you lined up in - and marched in, and - so many would march up - fifth to sixth standard would march up to this - this room, and then turn and go into their own room. And then when you came out at night you sang, Oh spre
a
d they covering wings around, every night. Any - in the - infant room, do you know what we sung in the infant? So we part, it may be never here to meet again. How in heaven to meet forever. Now that's no in hymn book you know, I was looking for it. It's n
o
 - that hymn was childhood shades are passing o'er us. Soon the days will - soon be gone, I forget, but it's no - it's out of the hymn book you know. But - that was the - parting thing. We kids - soon we part, it may be never here to meet again. Oh dear. 
No, they did not. Some of them wouldna could - they wouldna be even said - soon we part, it would be party, soon we party, maybe never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were your parents interested in how you were doing at the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I don't think so. Because - I never - I ne
ver - no, we didn't get - much encouragement - to - to do - no, no, no, we got our - our homework. We got homework. Maybe - maybe no when younger. But I know - in the - when I was - coming up at the fifth and sixth standard, well, we got homework and one 
t
hing I could never draw. We had to draw something a little large and something a little - draw it smaller, draw it larger. An we were drawing - well we'd this thing this day and it was to be drawn either - smaller - smaller or larger, I don't remember whi
c
h. But I rubbed it and I rubbed it - then - are you no near done yet? Get that - get that - hurry up and get that book away. Well you got a syrupy piece, syrup went on the drawing book. And needles to say - I never was punished for that. I think the teach
er had seen that - I would be beat, I - I tried. I - I couldnae draw. It was a thing like a railing and - oh - clouds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did the children in this school come from homes like yours or were there others from different types of home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Yes, there'd 
be some would - the Maxwellton children came across. They came from Maxwellton you see. In these days - the work was at this end of the town in the mills. You see. So that the mill workers who'd been - that they were all living at this end of the town, th
i
s would be the busy end of the town in these days. And quite a lot of children came over the Maxwellton side and they always got away at mealtimes ten minutes to one so that they'd be across the suspension bridge before the mill workers came across. Other
w
ise they wouldnae got across. You understand? Because the mill workers would be coming in mass, so that the children going away - from the school - ten minutes - before they would to cross the bridge before the mill workers came out. And - most of the - t
here was a good many mill workers in St Michaels Street and all round that district. And Henry Place and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 Wallace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have any sort of groups or gangs in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Nothing. Nothing at all. Occasionally - a potter would come to the sc
hool with his - bring his wheel and show you the - kind of a treadle and he - he'd make the wheel go and - his lump of clay, he set - a potter'd come into the school, might bring it. But that was all. A blind man sometimes turned up and he would work his 
Braille, we saw him working. The Braille. Yes. Let you see how the - the - did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did you ever find that there were children that nobody got on with at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh I don't think so, no. In the school in these days - there was the poorer children
 - that got their books for nothing, they were the - they were - on the Parish. They were the P.B's. The P.B's. That was the Parochial Burgh. You see? Well they were the P.B's, they got their books for nothing. The Girls Home of course they were - they go
t their books for nothing. But there was the other - the P.B's that - well the P.B's had to go out and get their exercises or their - their books, they were the P.B's. Well of course -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were they looked down on by the rest of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, you know
 they were - they were the P.B's. Oh I won't say they were, but - some of them werenae - were scruffy some of them, some of them were scruffy. And then there was a soup kitchen. In the wintertime - mind, in these days - working children - people's childre
n
 were pretty hard up, because in these days if there was no work there was no pay. And there was a soup kitchen. And - you could - children could get their soup ticket for nothing if they were a P.B! Or I think it was a penny or a ha'penny, and the soup k
itchen was up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Munches Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and - they got to go there and get their plate of soup and a roll and - for dinner time in the winter time. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you have any regrets about your education?
