Well, I left - when I'd be coming into my thirteenth year, I'd be twelve past. I - 
I would be - I would have had my thirteenth birthday, for I would leave in the June, we left in June. Some could leave at eleven. They were allowed to leave at eleven. My husband left at eleven, because his mother was a widow. And he left - to help her. A
n
d - and - these days widow, well she'd to make her living the best she could. She would earn - she - I believe she dressed and ironed collars and she took in a lodger. To help. And - she was left with three boys. One was a - had hip joint disease and the 
o
ther two was just eighteen months old when her husband died. And - she had come from a good family from Findhorn and had come - come down here and been in service - in outskirts in what is now the Embassy. And of course she fell in with this - shoemaker. 
H
e was a shoemaker as a shoemaker. He made the shoes. You see? He was a shoemaker to trade. And he was a shoemaker. Well - he died when - T.B. when the children were - my husband and his twin brother was eighteen months old. She was left with these. And th
e
 chap that he worked on the bench with came to have his own business in the town. So - but - shoemaker - made the shoes, I remember my father - now - an old dirty man in the road, and father says, he says, that's the finest - lady's shoe - that, he says, 
is the finest lady's shoemaker in the town. And dirty looking old man.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't go on to any other school?
