\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well - the
 - the only musical instrument would be a - a mouth organ, my father could - a wee cheap mouth organ he would maybe play. And he used to say I can play a bit on the mouth organ. But - I would be - what I would be - seventeen or eighteen before I got a pia
no I think. Here. I'd be seventeen or eighteen - before I went to learn the piano.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You say your father was a singer too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. And he - of course I was surprised when he bought the piano. There was a - a - a relative of our father's lived - in - 
the wee - you know - you know Forterrace at all? You know - you know - well the girls home, you know where the girls - where - where the Clebe House, well Gleve House there's a - a blacksmith there, there's a blacksmith there, on the corner. Well, there w
a
s always a blacksmith there. And in that cottage my father's uncle lived in that cottage. And they had a piano. And I used to go down one - and ask Aunt Mary, can I play the piano? Could I go in and play the piano, they had a piano. And I used to like to 
get along there and to play the piano. And - I could mind I tried to - to finger out Scotland Ever Dear, oh I liked that piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were there many books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
We weren't - we weren't allowed to read. Because - a novel reader would never be a
 worker, you see. You'd become a novel reader and you would - you would - you would sit down and you wouldnae work, you would just sit and read novels. Therefore you werena allowed - that was the reason, you weren't - I wasn't allowed to read, because it 
w
ould learn you to become a novel reader. It would make you a novel reader. Well - remember I got my - mother was ill and I was helping my brother - I was mangling the clothes, he was turning the mangle, and I was doing this spreading out and my - my thumb
 went in. And I got my thumb burst. And - therefore I - I couldna work very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me about the newspapers and the magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well there was - we got Alice Sloper, my grandfather bought Alice Sloper. Alice Sloper was a grown up paper. Alice Sloper's Half {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Holiday{\*\xmlclose}
. We got it to read. This Alice Sloper was a - a - it was a - father in one house, I - I canna remember, it was his wife. And all his family. And - and he went on his half holiday to - where would it be, in - in - out of London,
 where would he go - he went out of London, it was by the seaside somewhere. Of course it got known as Alice Sloper's half holiday. That was a great paper in these days. I canna mind much - about Alice Sloper. That - and - revolution of a younger daughter
 and those - those - there was a good few of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And your mother bought the People's Friend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I don't know if she - I think she bought the People's Friend but I'm no - I think she would. See they lent - they loaned each other papers and - I don'
t know whether she got the loan of some other - it was a monthly I think. And Good Words was a monthly thing. And - a lot of Ernest Ward's stories - came out in the People's Friend in - in parts. Alice Ward wrote for the People's Friend, that's where she 
got - she started in the People's Friend. And she'd - I don't think people would read Alice Ward's stories now, do you think so. I don't think - yes, they werena - they'll no be enough - wouldn't - they wouldna be exciting enough now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did anybody ever read aloud to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Read aloud. Well I'll tell you that childhood - Childs Own Magazine we - it was read aloud. I didnae enjoy it. It had - no, it had memories of what - what else I got for this - this book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you ever taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, you see, she was a stranger here. And I don't think - no - but in my mother's time - I - went with my mother and my mother - I haven't the least recollection of what she was like or anything, but you know John Laur
ie. John Laurie. John Laurie's - mother and my mother were friends. And - the Laurie's lived at that time in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brooms Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, in - opposite where the - where - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brooms Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, one of these houses. And I can remember - going - to - Mrs Laurie's with my mother -
 being in Mrs La}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 rie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
s and singing to her. Now - I couldn't have been very old but - that was - I can remember singing that. To Mrs - in Mrs Laurie's. Now that's a long long time ago. And I remember visiting in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Troqueer Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the Hetheringtons. Now my mother must have known the Hetheringtons. Visiting them there. But not much about it, but I can remember being - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you visited at Moniaive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh of course, that was my granny's. Yes, that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How often would you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well 
- the - for these letters - well I can't ever remember - well do you see, you hadna the chance to visit, for - it was the getting there and getting back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you ever taken out shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well - I think - eventually - you see - we would have 
our weekly grocery - we'd a weekly - grocery bill, but - if - you - you - you shopped in - St Michaels Street was a street of wee shops. And you fared very well in them. Now - next to the mill was - well, he was Macauley, but you called him - just Cauley'
s. You go to Tom Cauley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
s. But it's really - and he became Provost Macauley. He had been a foreman in the mill. And - he - had opened this shop and of course his wife kept the shop. But - him being a foreman in the mill, if - any of his workers dealt with h
im he would - could give them favours. And the mill workers - must have complained. So he got the chance of either - taking up - keeping his job in the mill and if he was going to have the shop he'd to leave the mill. So he left the mill. And - as I say h
e
 became Provost Macauley. And there was another one further along, he had been in the mill too. They called these shops huckster shops. They sold - they sold sweets - sweets and - it was like that, sticks, and Macauley sold teapots and bowls and - tea and
 
sugar no doubt and - a ha'penny draw. The ha'penny draw was - a wee box - Sedlitz Powder box, no as big as that but he had a box, and - he would have wee slips in it, written on it what - what - if you don't know what you was to get for your ha'penny, in 
t
he lid. Ha'penny draw, all prizes, no blanks. And that was in his window. Well, I'm in a mind indulging in a draw. Mind this was only once a week, but - you didn't - maybe be - I don't know what they got for their - their draws, a stud or - a golden stud.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You got pocket money once a week did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Hapenny once a week, and you could buy - get two ounces of sweeties for a ha'penny. Sweets of these kinds were fourpence a pound, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 pear drops}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 , conversations, butternuts, all that lot were - fourpence a p
ound. And - you - there was a shop for sweets you could buy you went to - to Borwns and bought the sweeties 'cos he just made a poke. Do you know what a poke is? Oh well he just made a poke and put a few - two or three sweeties in that for a ha'penny. And
 
of course sometimes he would - diverge, he maybe treat you something a - a bit of rock with that - ha'penny. Sometimes you'd buy a ha'penny bar of - of Fry's chocolate, which was think bar, or you'd go to Greens and get half of a penny bar which was a bro
ader - bigger bar, it was better chocolate. That was for your ha'penny. He had half a bar for you. So these were the things you bought. Or - or conversations. And you'd read the conversations, I love you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you ever go out with just your father, after he remarried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No I think we all went out together. All - all together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you ever go on any holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
There are all the holidays that I'm telling you about that I went to. Over - over to Hightae. Well - you see - my father never - work
 - workmen never had holidays. The only holidays they had - was one day. It was a spring holiday, maybe not. Now - for a - we would go in an excursion now - on the summertime Glencaple was the place where {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries
{\*\xmlclose} went on a good day. If it was a good time down to Glencaple. They would - July holiday was a great day because everybody was on holiday on the July {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Holiday{\*\xmlclose}
, was The holiday, and everybody had a holiday. And everybody went to Glencaple, with the - the - by this time there was wagonettes and charaba
ncs, horse. And - you made up a basket with sandwiches and a can, you made a fire and - and - had our tea. Lit a fire on the shore and - and had tea and - enjoyed yourself, we did, it'd be a day with a good tide, you see, and - see, on a Sunday if it was 
a
 good tide, we'd go to Glencaple for the day. And - again you took pieces. Now if cost you - I think - I think it - the parents would be a shilling return, and I think the kids would be sixpence. As far as I can remember. But all the - they - they would g
o down, they could start off at eight o'clock in the morning, the buses ran from - from the Plainston}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 s. Do you know where the Plainstones is?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 At St Michaels Bridge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. The - the buses started off from - where the store boutique is, where - where - where - it's the Courtnay Hotel in these days, it was the - it was the Commercial Hotel, but - nearer Assembly Street. At the top of what - they come up 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Assembly Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now. Well - there, that's where all the charas started there, and they turned down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Assembly Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and turned - our of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Ash Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then when they come over the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Irish Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} the horses had to get the gallop up to get the revs up to get them up the braw. Do you see? As they galloped down 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Irish Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and then up - to get up - to get them up the brae at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
St Michaels Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 you see. That was the - of course - they - they were running - the horses come onto the - on - onto the brae. Of course they walloped them up so that they - the - he horses got well up the brae before - because it was a good gallop up yon brae.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would be with a full load?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Aye, you see, for the horses, couple of horses. That would be - they used to gallop them up there. There - there was some of the charas I've seen with three horses in them you see. B
ut - later on as the charas got better - that was the gallop up. Now - I've known a horse - bolt. That was another thing that could be exciting - when a horse bolted, you see, to run away. Well I remember that a horse bolted - down the High Street, you se
e
, they couldnae come down the High Street for the bad turn. And the brae coming down the - bad brae, the turn. Well they come down and into - what's the old house - next to the Southlea church, you see what's facing you. The horse couldnae see if he was -
 
the horse had bolted. That - there was nobody to drive, well you see it - it crashed into the - the machine, whatever it - but there was a rearing up round that house. But - possibly the horse would have to be destroyed, I don't know but I know - I rememb
e
r horses - a horse bolting, from the High Street, and I think it was a good horse, or horses, and of course they wouldnae - could take the turn. They were going - and - there werena tarmacadam streets then, they were - granite sets or cobbles. Well you se
e
 down the High Street it came and of course it - it hadnae the - it couldnae take the turn, it crashed into the - into that - in that house at that time was - I think - Martin, the Town Clerk's brother, but it was - it was a private house then. Of course 
that's a house that's to be kept. It's - something - whether it's architecture or something. That was a great - oh a horse bolting was a great thing. A horse bolted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about Saturdays when you were at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well there was no Saturday - Sa
turday - oh well, I don't know what would happen on Saturday, that was a play day, Saturday, of course Saturday it was bathnight and - and then Saturdays - now you see Saturdays in life then - my father came home and he'd get washed after dinnertime and t
h
at and I don't know what would happen in the afternoon, but - but - my father used to go up the town. That - that will have to come into the - into the - into - into what went on in the town I think at that time, Saturdays. Because the - they - they went 
t
he messages up - the town then. And a lot of the shopping would be done in these days - from - the most popular that was round this South end of the town, I would say that - in this - in this side of Burns statue wasnae very much - they were more high cla
ss shops that the - as far as the square, that'll have to come - that'll have to be when we come to the - shopping and - and went on - what went on in the town. That'll have to be - another part of the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about Sundays then, church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well every Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had special clothes for going to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Now - my clothes would always be - be - I would be - I would be - maybe thirteen - or fourteen before I ever - except when I was a wee kid as I say getting this dress made, I'd be thirt
een or fourteen before I would - ever be at a dressmakers As far as I can remember. But my mother made my - my clothes. And I can remember when I was a - it was the time I worked with my grandfather, she made me this dress and it was blue stuff. And I don
'
t know, perhaps it was like lining, but I never - clothes didnae bother me because - well we'd cousins in London, father's sister who was sort of bitterly married and she - her father had - her husband was Scots draper in London and they came their holida
y
s. Of course they were all rigged out, we - nice clothes and all that sort of thing. So they - this day - they were down at our house, and I had just got this - new dress, this - new dress made. My mother had made this new dress. And - and - I got the new
 
dress on and I went out with them and the two of them were one on each side of me, and they're looking and they said was that a new dress? I said, yes. It looks like lining. I heard the kids - how nasty they could be. It looks like lining. Aye. You see, t
hey came - they could come with nice clothes on. Rigged out for the - holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you allowed to play games or anything on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
On Sunday? No. Sunday was a kind of dreich day. I don't know what we did on Sundays. I canna remember what we di
d on Sundays. I say, oh we went walks. Well of course you went a walk and then come back for your tea and - and - well - you'd go to bed early-or - but I - my father and - and - in his younger days, he used to read a wee bit out of the Bible, on a Sunday 
night, the - the book was put out and he would read a wee bit of the Bible, I won't say that we really - realized what he was reading, but he did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 The whole family went to church in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I - occasionally we - that - as I say my first vis
it to the church would be about with my father and it would be after my mother's funeral I remember sitting with him in the church. But - and after that I did go with my father. And - sometimes we all went of course - we went to church and then - I think 
-
 I think on the whole that - that mother went with us too. Needless to say - different times I'm going to - an odd time I'm going to St Michaels into the seat I sat in, and - looked round and - saw so and so sat there and who sat there and - and - in thes
e days we sat in all the different places. And - now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you see Sunday school always - when church came out you went into Sunday school. Church come out about half past twelve. And then you sent to Sunday school to half past two. And - and it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You must have been hungry by the time you got out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - that was - we - we got out about half past two. Now Sunday school got - it was a - right - they were all divided into classes. There were different lad
ies - that - took the - classes. Some of them better - was women about the town. And the class - the class that I was in was - Doctor Murray's daughter. She had this - oh I thought she was a - she was a great singer, I used to think it was great. She - sh
e
 could sing. And - she - didnae do her parents credit - in this respect, she married the - assistant minister which was - Alexander, and of course her parents werenae on with this, they would think she - she was too good for it. The - the - Doctor Murray 
-
 his wife I think would be somebody or - but - mind the doctor was stuck up then. This Doctor Murray - oh she was - it'd be against the grain that - that she got married to Alexander. And I can remember we gave her a - each subscribed a shilling, the girl
s
 gave a shilling and we got her a wee shell butter dish, it had a shell in silver, we got another - lady teacher that she was friendly with, a Miss Coupland, and she taught another class of girls, she lived in Mount Sindy, what Mount Sindy is now. She liv
e
d - yes, oh well she lived in Mount Sindy, I don't know what - I don't know what - but she would be quite well off person. Miss Coupland, and they were friendly and she - she bought this - this - thing. I don't think you was ever anywhere else but Longban
k, he was a nice looking chap. Alexander. And of course he had risen to the ministry, but his father was just - the joiner at Terregles you see, and he - he was wasnae somebody you see. His father was just the joiner at Terregles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Murray{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s thought it just wasn't the thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - yes. Oh no, that didn't - that wasnae - they weren't - werena very pleased at that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were there any other activities organised by the church that you went to?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 We didna go to the Band of Hope, quite a lot o
f the - the children went to the Band of Hope. And there wasna a - there was the Band of Hope and then there was the - the - the - Young Men's Guild at St Michaels, but we didn't - our people didn't - my father - and - well my mother - own mother had been
 
living he - I'd have no doubt he'd - because he would - he was - he had an interest in things - when he married this time. Before he married. And then - for a while he continued, then he must have given it up, for what reason I don't know. He was connecte
d
 with the temperance, there was a temperance association. And I think he was - he would be. Treasurer or something 'cos he used to sell some tickets and he had something to do with it. And - that was a - they had a social - a temperance social, that was a
 
- that was something to go to. But it wasnae dear that, it was threepence I think. And then - a great thing in the church was the conversazione, it was a shilling and - the ladies - the ladies all at tables and there was a great - they - they brought thei
r teapots and things. This was a - the conversazione, it was a great thing, I'd go just once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did they have any entertainment at that or did you just go for a cup of tea?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes - oh - there would be singing and that and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14419181\charrsid10313804 speechifying}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  at the conversa
zione. And the Sunday school then, the party - Sunday school, party was a cinematograph - a cinema - a magic lantern. It wasnae - a magic lantern, did you ever see a magic lantern? Aye well, it was a magic lantern. And - they would have a set of slides, a
n
d then they had some comic slides that we knew, we'd see it there every time that they - would see this - this comic, and it was a card thing and they - they could manipulate it that the - the - a chinaman that was dancing or doing something. And you went
 - and - your - when you came out you got a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 park in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 and an orange and an apple. That - that was your entertainment. That was the entertainment you got for the Sunday school party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was that at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Round about - round about the Christmastime
. But that was all the entertainment you got. Now the - the - the - the temperance social had a threepenny bag and you got - you got a bag of cookies and stuff. That was for your bag and - got that. But that was all the entertainment. And for the trip - S
u
nday school trips at St. Michaels - one year you would be taken by train to - a first station out of the town. And the second year - you'd get a - a walking affair to Hannahfield, down - down to the Crichton to the well, the artesian well, you would - it 
was a walking affair, you'd to walk - march. And you'd the whole day, you'd - your bag and milk, in the afternoon you'd have tea and you ran races.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You got your bag and your drink of milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Aye, and you had races and - oh and you - and the swings 
- you enjoyed it. And then you'd walk back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You'd be tired by that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, and then - at St Michaels had it - the parish, and it's large parish, it extended right out to Locharbriggs. The - that's what they called the landmark part of - of S
t Michaels. And it extended to - and they came in - and you'll have sometimes - have seen - Hutchins, Town Cerk in the paper. And I've seen him riding, because he - he - his father - was schoolmaster at the Landmark Parish and - he's - I've seen him but h
e's younger a wee bit - I can go even further back than him, and - but they used to come in in carts. You know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't have to walk all the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, they - they walked in from Locharbriggs. They would come in carts. And the B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 ownhall people 
- Brownhall was in this - in St Michaels Parish too and - they - they adjourned down to the - to the old field. They were - they were lent - they were loaned the field from the Crichton, and - and they'd take you down to see the artesian well. There's art
esian well - now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was the Crichton a hospital by that time or was it still a private house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
The Crichton was - the Crichton was erected as a - hospital. A - a - a mental institution.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I thought there was a big house there originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 N
o. No. No. The Crichton - now, the - the - Mrs Crichton of Friar's Carse, this - sum of money, you must learn - get the gen on that. And she - you can learn where that came from but this money came to her, and she - left the money - they - they were in Fr
iar's Carse, and the money she donated for - to make an institution for the - mentally - deficient, for mental - you must learn about the - about the Crichton - Crichton Royal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your father take any interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well he was a C
onservative. He wouldnae understand it, he would read the Herald but he wouldnae understand it. Sentinel was a - a Liberal paper but he took the Herald because it was a Tory paper. Oh he was Tory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he take an active part in politics then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I don't think - I wouldnae say so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He didn't have anything to do with the Conservative party?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - maybe - I don't think so, like - no an active, he wasnae - I don't think men were the same. They'd argue with each other but I don't think though th
ey - they didnae get on - like what they're - what they're now - what they're now. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Why do you think he was a Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You see, the - I don't know. There are still Conservatives and Tories and I - Tories and Liberals. You see? Well, the Tories - were more in the moneyed class I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You think it was because he had his own business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I don't know. - what it was. You see - I really - to me there shouldna be class at all. There's something - it was something to do with that. But I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you remember your father voting in an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Oh he would just - vote Tory. And - this - this now - this wasnae always a - it wasnae a Tory stronghold this, it was a liberal stronghold. I think always. A Liberal stronghold, of course now - there's Socialists, there's all things in it now -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about your mother, would she be interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Women weren't interested in politics then. Well they'd no vote you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She would have died before the vote came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh long long ago, dear me, it was - I was grown up before the voted came in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
There's some places that men felt they would lose their jobs or they might lose their houses if they didn't vote the same way as their employer, do you think that was like that here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I don't know, I don't think so, you see, I - well, there would be - men that worked - men that worked to - to the gentry, now - they might have followed their boss, they might have - they might. If t
hey were depending - on that place for their living they - they might have been - been - sort of felt they'd bound. Again - it's a secret what the - the - the - the gentry shouldn't have known what - they always had to hold their tongue. They could say wh
at they liked but they would have to be careful where they were speaking and what they were saying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When your parents weren't doing their work how did they spend their time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When they werena doing their work? They did their work and then they sto
p. Well you see they started work - well, my father's men, they in summertime start at six in the morning and they were off at eight. Back at nine, off at one, back at two and off at six. Or five - six I think. Five, I'll say five. And - I don't know what
 they did. I don't know what they did at night. Well with my father as of course I say had an allotment. And lots of men would have - would have allotments they would work. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He wouldn't go out to any clubs or pubs or anything of that nature?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was he interested in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I don't think he really had the time. I don't think so. I never mind him now - I never mind him interested. To be quite - you see - now do you see, from the first I ever came up here - my grandfa
ther died just after, we came up here after he died. And then - well my father would - would have to - carry on the business and - and then - losing his wife and his father, that I reckon that my father had a - I rather think he had an uphill job all his 
days. Now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you know if they belonged to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, well you see he was a - he was a - he belonged to the Ancient Order of Foresters, that was a Friendly Society. They paid into that. Now the rules if they paid into that you see
 a Friendly Society, when they were sick they got a benefit and - that was the only thing that he was in - he was in the Ancient Order of Foresters, they seem to have faded out. There was Foresters and Freemasons and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 Odd fellows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 , these are all friendly soc
ieties. That - they benefitted if they were sick - or if their wife died - he was never in an insurance - never in a burial society. That was a common thing. A burial society, they paid a penny or tuppence that was so that if he had a death he'd money to 
b
ury them. And I can remember - after - well - my husband's mother - because she had been in a Friend - in a - in an insurance - she paid a copper or two for - into the into the society. Well she would pay a copper or two into that. And I can remember - af
t
er we got married - let's see - a man came along and - and he wanted to - insure us into this - burial society. And - well I thought it over, my father says, now - he said, he didn't think it was a good thing for a man to have his wife insured. It wasnae 
g
ood. It wasnae good - it did - it wasn't a nice thing for a - a man to insure his wife. That's what he said. So - I was never insured. Well he thought it was - oh well I think he thought that a man could do away with his wife and get the insurance. One go
o
d bit of advice - long ago - quite - folks long ago had often - whisky in the house or port wine - at - well we never had never had, but when we got married and my husband he says - well we took up house. And - he says, do you think we should have a bit o
f
 - get a bottle of whisky and a bottle of port wine, in case anybody comes in? So I got this and - brought this in. So my father had seen it coming in. So he said to me next day, what was that you brought in last night? I said what it was. Well he says, i
f
 you'll take my advice - he says, anybody that's no - content with a cup of tea in your house - let them stay away. Take it away, never keep it. He says, it's - it's like fire. As long as it's in the fireplace it's all right. But, he says, it can get out 
o
f hand. Leave - leave it outside. So - I took his advice. And my husband was quite agreeable. And we never - we never had it and we never needed - we never gave anybody. He said, if a cup of tea'll no do, then, he says, you'll never have their company. So
 it was good advice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You got a lot of good advice from your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
He was good. Now - I can remember my husband - well - he was brought - he was brought up without a father, as I say, his mother - I was brought out - up without a mother. In - i
n the same terms. Well - he never mixed with - he was a sort of shy and - he had - with leaving the school at eleven he hadna the - he was - he would work, he was a good worker but - he wasnae a good mixer, you know. And - he - I can remember - St Michael
s
 were having something of party and he gave me - and we got invited to this - young folks party and he agreed to come - he would come to this party. This was before we were married. He would come to this party. And - so he came - and there was quite a lot
 
on the party that he knew. As I say he was never mixing, and he'd never been to parties or any of that. So - we - started, and then - and then - he didnae join in, I canna mind what it was but he wouldna join in. And - and he disappeared. Now he'd went aw
a
y out and left me, but he'd waited outside. Well I wasna pleased, I was let down. And then he - he just - just because he - he just didna like. Well he waited outside so when we come home of course I got out, I said, oh no, I said, this is no going to do 
m
e. And that's all. I don't know, we didna come home on very good terms that night. I felt, well - and this was - maybe a month or two before we were to be married. So - my father said when I come in - I come in - he asked about it. He must have seen - som
ething wrong, he must have detected something, I don't know what it was. Oh well, he said, what - what's like is up? So of course - I had said what had happened. And - I said, oh well, I said, - there were - there werenae - now - we were opposites. Well -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't have any part time jobs that you got paid for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 This was all the job ever I had. This was the only job ever I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You came here when you were about thirteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - I would be - I would be in my thirteenth year I think when 
I came here, to work to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You say he was old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, he would be coming - he would be - be - coming on eighty. I would think. Yes. He'd be coming on eighty. And of course - landed in this big house with no training or - well - you're just a 
lassie and you - you know. Yes, it was bad enough when I was grown up. Of course it was to - wash the dishes and - and - generally just - work away like that. Talk to - there was an office boy, talk to him when grandfather wasnae about then. And - but I d
o
n't - and - and I - I came away with my - and - came up with my father in the morning. Maybe we would leave home about - in the summertime it was half past six. I never minded coming in - any - but we always came away early in the morning because I think 
- my father used to come up and light the fire for him and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't stay here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, no, I slept at home. Stay - slept at home. Slept at home. And - I say I got three pound ten the first - six months. For the first six months, and then I was on a - a half a crown a week basis after that. Got two and six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Who's idea do you think it was that you should come here and help, do you think it was your grandfather's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. I don't think so, I don't know. I - I really never - knew, I was j
ust to come up here and - possibly - my father would think - you see, grandfather had never had a - a housekeeper for a long time, and I don't know whose idea it was at all. You see - in these days you got - you just did as you were told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would have no say in the matter at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. I was sent - go up - up - here and work to grand - go up to here and - wash the dishes and - and - wash the floor, as - do - do - do what there was in the house to be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about the washing, did you have that to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - no. I don't know - I really can't - remember whatever he did with his washing, but only once did I get - a washerwoman - that we got to - sometimes we had - and - I went for her and of course - the wash house was outside and a boi
ler, the boiler had to be lit and the - you know, water heated. And - and she was quite a - decent body this. But then she was using the washboard you see, there was no such a thing here. So I had to go away to her house - and - get her washboard. And - m
y
 grandfather - you see, he wouldna - he would never have approved of that sort of thing you see. I don't know but - but - you can never tell. But I do remember going to her house and getting the washboard so that she could get the washing done. What the w
a
sh was I can't remember. But - in later years, when we came to live here we had Mrs Joyce used to come in always do our washing. If - well - and I can't remember if we had her every week or once a fortnight, I just can't remember that. But I learnt a grea
t deal from Mrs Shaw. And things that - that - we would never think. So - I never remember - I never remember much more about grandfather's washing. What - how it was done or where it was done. I can't remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That wasn't your business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, we
ll I was - wasna interested in that. Further than - than that one time that I had to go and get this washboard and get - there were no - he'd his - day - times he went for his walk, and - I had to be away for the washboard while he was away for his walk. 
And have the washboard back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was he retired by that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Or was he still taking an interest in the business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, no. Oh well you see he was stone deaf, no he - no, no, he was retired. He was - he was retired. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about cooking, did you have to cook his meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. That was one thing I was well fed here. Because - he - he used to buy - bacon. You never see it now, the home cured bacon. And - cut - well he kept a - bit here and he cut off so much. Now there is no
body what would eat it now. And - well I was a big hungry lassie and he used to cut this - bacon in thick rashers, and - fry it in a pan, then he used to make what they called athel cakes. They were oatme}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 l - oatmeal pancakes, he called them athel cakes. A
nd fried these oatmeal pancakes in the pan and - and - that's what you got for your breakfast, a slice of this bacon and an athel cake and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You always got a cooked breakfast then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. Now I've a feeling that on a Sunday - he must have had s
ome - I didnae come on a Sunday. I think on a Sunday - he must have had a - a - a lady friend of some kind that come round here, I only surmise - because - he used to get - a leg of mutton - about every week, well - pretty often. Well a leg of mutton wana
e
 a wee scanty bit of mutton what you get now. It would be maybe - four or five pounds. This leg of mutton came, and that was always roast on the Sunday. And he used to have what you call a plum duff. That's a - what they call a clootie dumpling now. But h
e just called it a plum duff, it was a - you know, a suet dumpling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 With lots of fruit in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Well that was - that was - some of it would be reheated on a Monday. We was all - always plenty to eat. And a slice of this - plum duff as he ca
lled it, plum duff, either heated up and - and - and - in the oven with - milk or - he'd maybe put a chunk in and put some milk with it and that was heated and - and that was grand. When I think of the feeds we used to have. And I could eat. You see, ther
e
 was a big range here at that time. You know. And then sometimes - sometimes he would make rice, and he liked to sit and boil the rice himself. And he would - put the rice on in a pan and stir it and sit at the range and - stir this rice and maybe throw c
urrants in it and - oh we had a grand feed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He was quite used to doing things himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Had he been a widower for a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, he had housekeepers. Housekeepers. All his days. From - well - his wife died in '72. And - well this was - this would be in the '90 - '90's you see. Maybe - 1890 something. You see. So he - he'd house - he had a housekeeper in his day and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And then you came here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well I don't know whose idea it was that I came up here. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You say you got Sundays off, did you get any other time off through the week?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, no. Oh no, it was a - a - you just put in your day here and - went home about five o'clock. Went home about five o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about a holiday, did you ever get away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
We never had holidays, people in these days had never holidays there was no holidays. Maybe better off people got holidays, but there was nobody had holidays. The only holidays in these days were - maybe a day at Glencaple, if there was 
a - a big tide. And - in these days there was the spring holiday. And then the annual holiday was about the July. That was all the holidays. At that - in these days. Now - in the - some people would maybe go down to Glencaple, take rooms there, that could
 afford it. That was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And stay for the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, they - they - they - went to Glencaple as - as a holiday resort. A lot of people took a house or - went and stayed with people and paid their - paid their rooms and - and - but the majority - ev
eryday folks - took advantage of a good day. Now - say a day like this, if there was a good tide they'd then flock into Glencaple. The bus of course was running. There was plenty buses. Running to Glencaple. And - if there was - and the folk took sandwich
es, they took their - their kettle and - lit a fire and - made a picnic.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You didn't get very much money in your hands, were you able to keep what you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. I - I had - it was handed over. I never remember anything but - but - children hadnae 
much money then. Well we had - there was some bairns that were poorer than - than us and less well fed and less well clad, and they could get pennies to spend or ha'pennies to spend, but - they werena as well kept as what we were. But we hadn't much money
. We had a - a ha'penny on a Saturday. And - any - if we got any pennies from anywhere, we'd to save them. See, that has been in our - that come into our house when I would be - oh well I would think - I couldnae tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Quite a wee lassie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes
, and - the - any odd pennies we got we planked in there. Your name was scratched on it, see the - there was the three of us to put pennies in - or - ha'pennies. Most it was pennies. Well - you put the penny in, and when it got full father counted it out 
a
nd it was banked in the Stone Man. You see. Sometimes there were a bit sticky paper or stout paper stuck on with your - a W put on it or a G or whatever, whoever's penny it was and of course you got your pennies out, and they went the Stone Man, and that 
- that was your - you didna think anything about it
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 The Stone Man is the savings bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Savings Bank. Aye. Aye, we'd all - we'd all books in the Stone Man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
How did you get on with your grandfather when you were here, was he nice to work to? Was he easy to get on with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Now you mind remember the kind of upbringing I'd had. He - he was - he was - I never - I'd no - well I - I wasn't a - I wasnae a - a fussy or affectionate, I'd lost that. But - in fact I - I used to - dodge him and - you know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Tried to keep out of his way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Well as I say - there was an office boy in the yard you see. Well if I could get talking to the boy he'd - somebody - he'd be somebody to talk to. Thirteen, what was it - what was you to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was he about your own age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - he - he's left the school. And you would talk to the boy and of course my grandfather - him being deaf, he could - you could shut the door and he didna hear and you could be elsewhere doing all kinds of things. Quite - quite i
nnocently now, I can remember once - one occasion. Getting the boy into - my grandfather - that was a sitting room in there, and he went for his sleep, I can mind bringing the boy in to show him something - to show him a - an album or something. As innoce
nt as if it was my own brother, sat there - and of course - get the boy out before - grandfather appear. Absolutely nothing in it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But you still felt you had to hide it from him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh - I would have got - chased with a stick. Oh that was - now wha
t my - and then if my - if my father got - speaking to the men that - who had been down there then, that was another row. Again - I didna - hadna - didn't see anything wrong in that. But of course my father did. He didna want me - but you were innocent.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You just saw them as somebody to speak to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, and they chaff - went - and - chaffed the men. Of course they were men and he knew what - what I didna know. No, no. And that - that boy I can remember - how I got the money for - buying that - buyin
g wool and knitting a - a - a scarf, like a - a - a knitted scarf with three pins for a present for that boy, how I got - what it was like I don't know. It was done here. On the sly, and given - this - scarf to Joe for his Christmas. I don't know, but Joe
 got that scarf.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 If you had had a choice would you rather have had another kind of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I never gave it a thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You just accepted that that was what you were to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Just accepted it. Never - never gave it a thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So how
 long was it you were here? Looking after your grandfather, would it be until he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. No, no, no. Oh well I can't remember that very well. Might have been - it might have been a year, I might have been - the year and a half. I might have been th
at. He went away to London for a holiday, and his daughter was in London. She'd her own family. And - I might have been - the first six month and then the next year. I might have been - or part of the year. 'Cos he went away for a holiday, I never remembe
r - I never remember - really coming - staying - going - leaving, no coming back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So what did you do after that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, I would be at home for a while because my stepmother had got into bad health then. And I would be at home. She would need me at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did you get on better with her when you were working here and just seeing her for a short time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, I couldna - I couldn't say - well, it were different for I wouldnae be so much - beside her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You wouldn't be under her feet all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. No. I think that - well I would think that I would get on better. I was just thinking - we once went - out to Carlisle, when that was - she went - paid a visit to Carlisle, we - we - we went once a holiday to Carlisle, she'd a sister t
here, and we went to see her once. And she'd another sister who was in - who was a maid in a house there and that was - we went to see - we - it was just - in Carlisle. And I can remember that was - the - the - the first time I'd ever been away from homel
i
ke - a trip like that. And we - I - well I get into bother there because - this sister that was in this place, she wouldna - couldna get away from her place at a certain time and of course - they would be anxious for to - for me to be in time for the trai
n, of course - I can mind getting a row at the station for - being - I couldn't help it, I couldnae come away. See, it was this - sister that had over - hadnae come in time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But you managed to get the train back all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about your friends when you were about fourteen or fifteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you see much of your old schoolfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well there was only - I had very few friends, the - they were - they lived away a wee bit away and a - an odd time I would ask - co
uld I get - get away and we would get away. They lived - they were down at Nithbank. Well of course there was always a time - if you were away to be back at a certain time and - and - well there was a row if you wasnae back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They were quite strict about that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
The things that I done wrong I seem to remember. Remember - that - that - I remember - there was jam boiling. Now - I shouldn't have - if she needed my help to - with the jam was a boiling I shouldn't have been away at all. Wel
l to - to be away and be back at a certain time, well of course I - I was down there and the jam was made. But very - getting - getting away - down to Nithbank, well of course - by the time you got to Nithbank and had a - play or - a caper, well - oh the 
time was gone, yes. But these are funny things that - these things - stick in your memory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you ever allowed to get your friends up to play at your house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Oh no, they wouldnae want to come. They wouldnae want to come. No, there place was
 a - an open air place, oh their place was - near round the country, it's away round about the - beyond the infirmary. The infirmary now, it's down there you see, it was - it was outside, you could - oh I don't know, we wouldna be doing very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had some space to run about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. And - and - I can't remember what - we just had our share of each other's company. And I canna remember very much about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You told me once you used to go round to a girl's home and play in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh that - oh that was at school, that was after schooltime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't keep up with any of the girls after you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh that was - that was after school - the school hours, that we - it was when you were at school that you - you could - perhaps t
he girls could come up at night. And of course we lived near them you see that you could go round and - if you saw the girls out well, if the matron would allow you you could get up and get a swing, this swing was a great attraction. But - oh I knew lots 
of the girls after - we left the school. But never - make friends with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did your parents know your friends at Nithbank, even though they didn't come up to play at your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes, they knew - oh yes - mother knew - know where I - where - 
who I was away to see. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did she ever say who you were to play with or who you weren't to go about with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you see - there was none I would - none - none of them in my age round about the district where we lived, you see. That these wer
e the only girls that I did take up with. Oh when we were little - you were told there was - characters that you hadnae to have anything to do with. You see - the Barnslaps now - and the Barnslaps in these days, well there was a - a person and she kept co
ws. And - she had a daughter, Kat e McClue. Well I had to have nothing to do with Kate McClue, because I knew Kate McClue wouldna be clean. And yet - they'd cows and they kept the milk in a wee place off the kitchen. Oh the hygiene.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you weren't allowed to play with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh I'd be forbidden to - to have anything - we didna buy milk from Kate McClure. But - I've been in Kate McClure's house where she kept the milk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How old would you be when you first came in contact with your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You knew him at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Oh yes, I knew him at school, he was in my class at school, of course he left the school before me and then - he became a butcher's boy and he used to come up our stairs to the next door neighbour for orders
 and - but I wasnae interested in him. Didnae think anything about him. And - I would be - I might have been - eighteen or nineteen - might have been twenty - oh I could have been - I could have been twenty. Anyway - before I - before I met him in this we
e shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 By that time your mother had died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh she - oh yes. I'd be here. Oh I had been here - oh - of course, we came here in 1901, and she died - she was only a week here when she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You actually moved here before she had died, I thought
 you came here after she died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Gran - grandfather died - grandfather died - about the day Queen Victoria was buried. Now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That was 1901 wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Because I was sent - they needed things for to dress him with you see and every pl
ace was shut up. There wasna a place I could get anything. I was to go and look for - I was to get a pair of white stockings and nightshirt and that sort of thing. And - the only place I could get it was a pawnshop. Of course the pawnshop sold - goods as 
well as pawn. And I can remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Things that people hadn't claimed back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, they sold new stuff. Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes, they kept new stuff as well as - as well as - all the - is the pawns - of course the pawns, you'd - they'd keep it for a year
 before they could sell it. Pawned stuff. But oh now, they sell - they sold everything, they sold - clothing, gents - all kinds of things. Oh yes. And that; was the only place that was open the day Queen Victoria was buried, well I think he died the next 
day. You see. And - then - after the funeral we came up here. Now - my stepmother died on the twenty-third of March. We came up here - we were just one week here when she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But she hadn't been in good health for a while before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Consumpti
on - Consumption - T.B. Oh what a pitiful disease. Pitiful disease.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you would have your hands full then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you didna think it - didna think anything about it. Well here mother was here when she died, her mother came. She was here when she died. And then she went away and then we were on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you looked after your father and your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Aye, well - you know what it would be like, he must have had a handful, well - he would have enough to think about. With losing his wi
fe and his father. And - and - the - and - he would - he - with taking over the business and - and - he would have plenty to think about and - and - and then us let off the chain. You were - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you feel like that when your mother died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You felt free then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - well - well you just felt free. Nobody to - bother you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you enjoy being your own boss then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I - you didn't think anything about it, you just got to - just a great big - uncultivated - and we were all alike. Of course there was the wee brother. There was the young brother you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He would miss his mother more than any of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Well I don't know. Well he would only be about three. No - he was born in - in '96, the end of '96.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He would be four and a bit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So that really you had a family to bring up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, you didnae think about it, you - you werena thinking about it. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You just didn't question that this was what you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No. I c
an remember trying - making him a blouse - out of a - well, he'd - mother - that's one thing, she - she made - all our - clothes out of anything you know, she - she made the best of anything she'd to - to make. You see. Anything she - and - she'd made thi
s
 wee - drill - blouse out of a - she'd seen a pattern. So - I thought I would make him another and I - certainly made no such a bad job of it, the blouse. See there was a sewing machine and I learned to work a sewing machine. I wasnae just a - I would - I
 would say I was more advanced than a lot of girls - that -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Possibly from having had to work in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. But - you'd - you'd an old head on young shoulders. I would say that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 All the same it would be quite a responsibility to look af
ter a young boy like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I don't - remember - never remember it being so. Never - never - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did the way that you spent your spare time change once your mother died? Did you go out at nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh no. No, no. No, no, we never - I never - 
there wasnae much going out because these girls I was with, they were - they were - these days - girls did more or less what their parents - what they were allowed to do, that - that any girls that - the girls that I did chum with, well they were just lik
e myself, they werenae - no like the girls nowadays, flying about, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would still see some of your friends though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you go visiting then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - when are - what are you - when you - when you could get off, or get awa
y or get out. Well - part - later on - Sunday, well - I think - I can't remember much where we went - then to the church so much in the forenoon but I know on a Sunday night - of course that was a - Sunday night was a night off that you went to church and
 - and then - when church came out on the summer nights - people went walks. And a favourite walk was away round the Mile House, that was - there were more people about the town on a Sunday night than there is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you would actually keep up with your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did they come to the house after your mother died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. I - I never - I never - liked that - I had the freedom. I never - I was - I sort of afraid of my father. I think he had a - had a - a kind of - I don't know what it would have been - kind of - there wasna many people came about the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He liked to keep himself to himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I think so. Never mind him - I had nae - I never - I never liked bringing my girlfriends here. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Mr Sturgeon's home was very much different from yours wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - of course he had a mother. And of course when - when I got - to know - Willie, well - she was a - a very nice wee body, she was - she'd come from the North. From Findhorn, she belonged to Findhorn. And she - would - be - she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 table maid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 at Woodlands. What's now the Embassy. And - he - my - well her husband belonged to Marshaltown, well - she would meet them. But they got married there. That's where she would meet him. But she was a - she - her father bein
g a master baker in Findhorn, but of course - girls had to find work to do as well. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It seems a long way for her to come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
But then she would come with the family. They'd be - she would be - a - a good family would come to take that house you see. In fact it was a fairly - Fairey's the Sugar }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 firm}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  that she was with. Fairie, Fairrie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
So they had a house up North and then they bought this one, and they would bring some of their stuff with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - I don't know - she - it was - tha
t was the firm she - she was - girls took places in all kinds of - big houses then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Where did they stay when you came to know them later on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh they stayed in Swan's Vennel which is - finished, it's out. They would stay in Swan's Vennel then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Where was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Off - off {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St Michael's Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Swan's Vennel opposite - not quite near the church but - opposite St Michael's church, where the new flats - the new - new flats there. I think they're - run by the town, the old people's - fl
ats. That was the Swan's Vennel. Now - I said before - that - a lot of the population at St Michaels Street would be - the houses would be built for the workers, because the work in the mills. And at Swan's Vennel there was any amount of - houses - with -
 maybe one or two apartments but it was to house the workers. - All the - the workers living - they, well, needed the accommodation that - these houses would be built for mill workers. A lot of them. And her house - was one of the nicest in Swan's Vennel.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was it just a small one too though?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
It was upstairs and she had - it had a room and a kitchen, and a - one back room. Of course there would be people up above that entered round - the - the other way. They would enter from behind, but - they wer
e up above her and her - she had a good outlook in her house. Again it was just an ordinary room and kitchen and a wee back room. Well - what - if I went down there I've seen she would put the room fire well, on a winters night that we would be sitting in
 the room, she would - well Willie never came here but - I would -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You used to go down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I'd go - go down to their house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you remember the first time that you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No. I can remember - that - the - his mother went a
way up North. She went North to Stuartfield, to visit - a - her sister had died, she'd be away for a wee while and Willie was on his own. And I can remember that I went down there and - and - cleaned up the house, see, there'd be nobody in it. I can remem
ber going up there and - clearing up her house - ready for her coming home. Which was - a great big step - but I think I'd made - I'd met her in - oh I'd met her before that. I - I knew her before that. -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She wouldn't let a complete stranger in would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well she wouldn't - she'd got no option because - I'd said to Willie that I would come down and - I went down this afternoon and - and cleaned up her - her house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was it usually a Sunday that you went to visit there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh he Sunday night
 that she put the fire on and we would sit - sit in the sitting room and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did they leave you on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Oh yes, yes, she just the fire on and went away and we just - we sat on our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And just talked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What sort of person was she, was she easy to get on with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
She was a - well - I say, she was - I - different, she was of a higher standard - than the people she lived among, she was - well spoken. You see, she'd come from a good family, her father and mother, sh
e'd - there was just three sisters with them. And she'd been well brought up, she was well-spoken, and been in a good place. She still - retained that. A - a - she'd a sort of superior air about her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So really she was only living in that place becaus
e of her family circumstances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Oh she was - she was - she was a - she wasn't the same }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 calibre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 as the people she lived amongst, she'd just that wee bit of something. Superior.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you think she had much to do with the people round about then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh she would - oh no, no, no, she would get on all right with the people round about but - but - she would have her - her ain business and she would - and as I say, she used to wash and dress collars. And - that would - make the little extra money. 
She didna tell me that but I - I met a girl - another man's wife and she says she had - used to deliver the - her - her - by the time that I got to know her well - she would be a wee - in a wee bit better circumstances. Well Willie was - be bringing in hi
s wage. But - this - other man's wife said she used to take round the collars for her. She lived in the Vennel too. And she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 said she}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  used many a time used to deliver the - the - the collars she dressed. Used to be collars on dickey's. I don't know if you ev
er see - did you ever see a dickey. Do you ever see a dickey? It'd just be a wee bit front and stiff, the collar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
That sort of thing would be more advanced than taking in ordinary washing would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, well yes. Well she would - yes. She w
ould have - could do that - she wouldn't have facilities to do ordinary washing. No, she never took in washing but she would dress a shirt - white shirts. Well - starch the white shirt and dress it, and collars and that sort of thing. But idea - maybe - w
ash and iron a collar for a penny. Just think of it. Fourpence for - for maybe dressing a shirt. Four pennies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was your husband's family churchgoers as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Granny was. Well - boy, well - daddy - I don't suppose - the boy, well they'd go in - th
ey might go to church, oh yes, but - as they got - the boys got older well they werenae so fond of going to church. But he'd been brought - they was brought up in the church. Because - they went to the Martyr's church and - the minister asked them - now -
 
they were - they - they wasna identical twins, so there was two of them, one was like the mother and the one was like the father. So the minister, Mr McKerra, he says - which was the oldest and - and Hugh said he was the eldest. How much older are you? Si
x weeks. He was six weeks older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You often visited down there then when you were courting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would be mostly Sunday - Sunday. Or Sunday night.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would they treat you just like one of the family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well they - well - of course - the 
- the other brother I don't - he wasnae there, he wasnae at home at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That was the older one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well the six weeks older one. Oh Hugh wasnae there then. I think - I think he'd gone abroad by that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How did you get on with your mo
ther-in-law after you were married? Was she the kind that would give you help or give you advice and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I got on - no difference, I - the only difference, I feel now that I could have been a lot - again, the way I'd been broug
ht I wouldnae have been but - she was a good granny. She was - she was - I'd no fault to find with her. Sometimes I used - I didna like - she was a wee bit - as if she would - like to know things. And - well you see, I had to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did she interfere a wee bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Not with anything but - but - I used to think - 'cos I never bothered my neighbours here, and of course she was living amongst neighbours. No, on the whole - she was quite a nice person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What did you call her after you got married and before you had children?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I never called her anything. Of course - of course when - when - when Wally came she was granny, then it was easy. She was granny after that. But I never called her anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you remember the first time that Mr Sturge
on came home here to meet your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No, I can't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But when he did come eventually your father was quite pleased with him?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
There were no difference. No. I couldn't say they could find any fault. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They got on quite well together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Well they didn't see that much because - he just worked in - at - at - the time he got to work, he done - he done only maybe a couple - might be home coming in here but - he'd be quite - he was quite - made quite welcome, th
e six month before we were married he was - a lot here. And I'm quite certain that my father wasnae displeased. And I really think that he would be quite - see that - it maybe wasnae what he would have chosen for me, but - he reckoned I would be better wi
t
h - you see, well I told you about - about the - the events coming from St Michaels and it was - oh well, then, that would be - that would be about - two or three month before we were married. I wasna having that. No, no, no. So - he said, well - as he sa
i
d that - I would - once you're home - that if you have a husband that's willing to stay in the house - you - you maybe - the time comes you cannae get out. He wants to go out. But you'll be better off with a husband that still wants to stay in the home wi
th you. And that was his advice. And I never - I never - my father - was sensible man. And I never - regretted - ever taking his advice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Do you think your father would know Mr Sturgeon's mother before you started going about together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Oh no,
 no, no. And - again - my father - now - that - that again - he didnae make - he - I didnae think - he wasnae a friendly person my father. And granny came up here, well - I didnae like - I was glad when she didna come because he didnae speak much to her. 
He didnae make her welcome. And - the only time she came was on a Sunday. There were - by this time her sister had come - from the North to stay with her. And - they werena of the - you see, my father - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804 w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 ill say - there's no maybe so much of it now but ther
e was - there - there were - no the same class as us, we'll just say it that way. And I've no doubt - that - that - as regarding - that Willie was of - he - he used to feel - he'd be better to let me go with Willie than to resent it, he might regret. He -
 he would possibly know that it would be no use him - saying - and I was better with a decent fellow, of a poorer - out of a poorer home than a - I would never have one out of a better home that was a waster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Like the one you were talking about last week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Did you manage to see much of Mr Sturgeon when you were courting, apart from these Sunday nights visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, because you see - there was no - there was nae half days, it was work, work. Which - six days a week, you were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You wouldn't come into contact with him when you were going for butcher meat or that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, he was in a van.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you more or less just saw him at weekends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you remember going on any outings when you were courting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I told you - about that - that outing to Keswick. That was one. And another - another one - we went was to Brodick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Arran{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. That - that was a Freemason's outing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was that just on one day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 One day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It's a long way to go just for a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I - I was - I like - I like to see that - view - that picture of that outing. That was a Freemason's outing, now - my father was a Freemason so I don't know what - I don't know where Willie would get the ticket for that, but - 
only - whether it was me, it would be me that was going and he would come with me this time. We went this outing to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Arran{\*\xmlclose}
. Now, that could have been the - summer that we were married. Like the - the summer before we were married. But I said he wasnae a mix
er. You know. Then the St Michael's do, well he - St Michaels do happened of course after that, but - he - he wasnae a good mixer. Now any - he knew any amount of the people. It was - at this - thing. And here we were going to have our - group - photograp
hed. And he didnae come in amongst them. He stayed away from the room, kept away out of it. Well I didna like that. I remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You feel he should have been beside you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - he could - but there was other men there that he knew and he - I don't know why he did that sort of thing. But he - he kept - he kept out. Just disappeared. Rather than getting amongst the crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about your food when you were on a trip like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That would be laid on I expect. I expect so. Oh I think - that
 would be laid - it would be in the - I can't remember about - very much about the food in that - that outing. I can only remember - it's quite a good picture yet, I like to see - but that's quite a good picture. There'll no be very many of them alive.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
When you went to Keswick he bought you a present, did he buy you anything when you went to Arran?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Aye, we - I don't think so. I don't remember anything at all. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you think he was saving all his money by that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. I think we we
nt - no, we went to - now where did we sail - I think we sailed - I think we had our meal in Saltcoats and we had to sail from Ardrossen, I think we sailed from Ardrossen - across to - to - to Brodick. I think that was it. But - it would be all laid down 
on the ticket I think, I - but I think - I think we'd the - the - the - the - the meals would be at - at a place in Saltcoats as far as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Can you remember a time when you decided you were going to get married, the two of you? Did Mr Sturgeon actually say, will you marry me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I told you he gave me a ring in a present. In his - it was a Christmas present, he didna say, he just handed me this ring, my Christmas present. Yes, I think he did say - but I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you think he would ask your father's permission first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. No. When - when we'd agreed that we would get married - he went and asked my father. He did. So my father just told him that it was - that that was for us to decide really, he would leave that to ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did it come as a surprise to you that he wanted to marry you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Or did you know what was in his mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Aye, and I think - in a way I was - I - I - I was rather it - it had to come. Because remember that - that - och I - I don't know. I was quite happy - without the marrying business coming in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get engaged as we know it today?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I got - I got - I tell you I got a - I got the ring in - before I was asked. That was all. And I wore it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You wore it on your wedding finger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Aye. That was all. I don't suppose you would know - or - he was a greenhorn he was green.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you get any presents when you got engaged then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I wish you saw the presents we got when we were married. Far less get - getting - presents when we were engaged. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What kind of presents did you get when you were married then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
From one person I got two hat pins. There were all - everybody had hat pins in these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They weren't just ordinary ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well they were different - 
kind of fancy ones. That was all. Oh dear me. Well Willie got lots of things from - people, customers, wee dishes that were of no - and people - people hadnae the money. We got - half a dozen teaspoons from - one person. This - they werena good teaspoons 
but - they were - well - but I think you accept - you did accept it you know, now I got ten shillings from my mother's mother, my granny gave me ten shillings and I bought a wee clock. Well my father said what - he thought I should buy a }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 wee clock}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  with it. 
Well I bought this wee clock and it was quite a wee wooden clock. A wee thing, about that - it do for a bedroom }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 mantelpiece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . I got a pound from an uncle and I bought a - I think it was a spirit kettle or a lamp, it was a useless thing but - they were thing
s that you bought. You - you - it was a - a - it wasnae a brass kettle, it was a kind of oxidised affair of a stand, and a wee spirit lamp. Well, these are kind of things that you had for - you made your tea and then you - that was the hot water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did 
you have a bottom drawer then, did you start and save up linen and stuff before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - my bottom - my bottom drawer was - I made my trousseau from the - it was about September when we decided to get married. Then I - my father said that - let - get busy and get my things away. And I made - underclothing. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You made all these yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. I'll let you see the nightdress I made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You've still got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I have that. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about other clothes, did you get 
other clothes made for you by that time at the dressmakers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I got my wedding dress and my costume made at a dressmakers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What was your wedding dress like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
It was made well - being a - a wintertime my father says, well get - get something t
hat you could - that'll be of some use. Cream crushed velvet. And - now - I had - well the dressmaker said - when I was to go and get fitted on - I just a - a lace petticoat, kind girls all - a white lace petticoat, it's all I can remember in this white l
ace petticoat which - I don't know where it came from, I - I never remember }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 buying}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  it, it was there. And - she - advised me to - she would send away and get me an underskirt, that was the first underskirt and it was a white - I got corded and pleated satin 
underskirt. It came - in - just in time for my wedding. To were under the - because - I don't suppose I knew what girls were wearing, I wasna - never near anybody. But - this - Miss - Hendrick, she - she'd be with Barbour. The first - costume that I had e
v
er made was made at Barbours, now that would be away about 19 - 1903 or - I could date - I can date things by the - the clothes I was wearing. In 19 - I got a black alpaca dress for mournings of course. In these days when anybody - lost anybody, mournings
 
was the first thing that come into their the mournings, the very first thing they thought about. Where will they get their mournings. And - about this - my - father's cousin made me this black - black alpaca dress. Well that was the first year. The next y
e
ar you got a second mournings, which was a grey thing. Again, that would be 1902. So I would think it would be - 1903 that I would get this black alpaca dress - my father sent me to Barbours to get it. This black alpaca dress. Oh no, black - it was black 
h
opsack and it - well you ken what hopsack is I know but - it was black hopsack, it was made with a bolero. And a blouse. Quite a - oh a right - nice thing it was. Wee - bolero. Wee tabs and wee brass - things on the tabs. And - now - a blouse to match The
 blouse made too. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Barbours had dressmaker's on the spot had they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - Barbour had two dressmakers at that time. They'd a Miss Graham. She was a big handsome - stately woman. Oh Barbour was - Barbours the place then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did they just do 
made to measure things like that or did they have dresses already made up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh the - no, very few - there were very - oh - dresses were all made. There might have been some ready mades, but - if you - with dresses that were made on Barbours premises. 
And Miss Graham was - she was a - a big handsome woman you know and she was always dressed in black satin. And she had a sort of rather strong voice, kind of like man, but no so rough but - she was a - big handsome woman. And - and - and she was always dr
essed in black satin and dignified and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Was she the sort of person that when you went in there you accepted what she told you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Now - no, no. No, no, when you went - if you - Miss Graham was the one - was the - they got the second one - at a late
r date but Miss Graham, you would go to see Miss Graham, and she would help you decide what you should have, or she - would find out what you - what you would like and she would sort of - oh no, she helped you to decide - what - what kind of material you 
