ant - and - did all the rest of it. And I don't think she would do any of the measuring, I don't think so. But maybe - no, no, I think she would have a girl that would - would come up and - and - maybe she took measures, I don't know, I can't remember, bu
t
 - she was the dressmaker in Barbours. Oh yes. Miss Hendrick, I think she'd been with another firm at - Miss Hendrick came into Barbours, and she was - maybe wasnae such a popular one as - but she was quite nice person. And - that was - she made that - co
s
tume. It was her that made me the - costume and the blouse and things. And - Now the reason that - and it was at that time that I got a hat - the same as Miss Chillen. And that was - and that costume the first time I went to visit my granny at Moniaive an
d
 that was the first time ever I visited her - from - from my mother dying. And I can remember going up in the wagonette with her. And I had a hat on and there was a lady and gentleman came in and they were in the wagonette too. And the lady had this very 
same hat, every way the same, but her roses were tea roses, mine were pink. The; very same hat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What sort of hat was it, one of these big ones with lots of roses on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, it was just a - you see, you went in and - and chose your shape and then
 the milliner - changed all the trimmings, you chose the trimmings. Now - these hats were got in the Steeple, in a shop in the Steeple. And the - and the person that made - made these hats is now in Devorgilla Home. A Miss Murdoch. And she's away - well u
p in her nineties. Now - my - I got a hat, an we - I went - we got - and shaped - and she got a hat there and - we all got hats there and the same - now the same style of hat - but different trimming. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you quite clothes conscious by that time
 then, were you interested in new clothes and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh just - oh - but - it was - you only got one thing, your Sunday frock, that was all. Oh yes, you'd be quite interested in your dress. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You said when you got your wedding dress you got a costume as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was that for going away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. That was - yes, I wore - I got - by this time I got - my hat for that going - for my going away hat, I got it at Miss Wier's down here, where Mrs Robettson is now, it was Miss Weirs the
n. Well she succeeded Miss Wier. Do you know Mrs Robertson? That place. Well she's a milliners shop down - the bottom of the High Street. Aye, well - she succeeded Miss Weir. She came to Miss Weir as a girl and she - fell into the business. But - I got a 
hat from Miss Wier. I'm sure I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
What did you wear on your head when you got married, did you have a veil or did you have a hat?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I was married in the Kings Arms. I wanted to be married in the church and get - church weddings weren't popular t
hen. No. No, no. Only a rare occasion - that somebody would get married in a church. It was quite common to be married - at the Manse the common place to go to the Manse to get married, or in a hotel. But - I've always been of a religious nature, and I wa
nted to be married in a church. But - I don't know - it fell through - well, I'd no mother. And because it - and what made it - to make it awkward. Now my chum was going to be my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15487441\charrsid10313804 bridesmaid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . But she drew out, I - I really - the - the church part fell throug
h and I was married in the Kings Arms Hotel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You must have been quite disappointed about not being married in the church?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - you didnae - you accept it - these things, you don't - didna feel disappointed but I - I'd looked forward to being married in the church. I felt that's where I wanted to be married, but I was - but no - you just accepted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you were actually married in the Kings Arms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
In the Kings Arms Hotel at one o'clock on Christmas Day, 1908. And it was a lovely day. It was a lovely day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Had you a big wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
There was twenty-two - twenty-two, that was all that I can remember, twenty-two people there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That was just immediate family was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, just - just - uncles and aunts and - now - I've kind
 of forgotten - exactly who was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was your grandmother from Moniaive still alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But she didn't come to the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh she wasnae invited. My - my Uncle Andrew which was my mother's brother, he and his wife was invited
 but his wife wasna well and she couldn't come and my cousin came and stayed. My cousin and my uncle was there. And - I - I really - there was one or two outside people that we were acquainted with was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have a bridesmaid eventually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
