\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He wasn't working for himself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He was still working for the other man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. No, he was - he was - working for another man. And - he was away all day, more or less and then - Willie didnae get the attention that a child should have got with me having - the books to keep and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And an invalid on your hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well at that time - my father didnae come home 'til the back end, maybe October. And he just sat a
bout. But - well I'd nobody here, and nobody - to sort of guide me lines how to bring up a baby. There no - you see - it's no bother to them now. To - to bring up children now, oh no. They have - they - they've real - they've come to realize - how - how e
a
sy it is. Now when you think when the children - born - died in infancy, it's deplorable. You go to the old churchyard there. They did in infancy, dozens of them. Oh it was terrible. What used to hurt me was this. - convulsion fits, well they're - you nev
e
r hear such a thing. Did you ever hear about convulsions? Aye well - well - the - that was the bogey bit. But you see Willie - he was a good baby and as long as you left him he never bothered, but he didnae get the training. What - a child should have got
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't have any bother with him having fits or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, no, but that - but these were the kind of things I think that bothered - other - bother - yes, but he was never any bother, no bother whatever. He would sit and - as long as he
 was happy he would sit in his chair, which if I had writing to do well that suited me, but then that was wrong. But - you realize - what - what - things go wrong that you don't realize at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was he a good baby through the night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh I nev
er remember any bother with him through the night, never seemed to be any bother with them through the night, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Your husband didn't get up to them through the night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well, we - we - well - I think in - to do - I would be the kind of lead
er but - no, no, he always - did his share, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about Sundays, did you all go out together on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well now, that's a difficult question. Because again - again I say at that time - at that time - later on we did, after children grew
 up. Well of course my father died - in 1911 - and - well I had everything to do then. And - but after the children rest of them came and grew up we used to go great walks. People don't do that now, but used to in the summer day we'd get them - them into 
the pram and be away - miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You all went together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. But that was the done thing. Long ago. That was the done thing with families, they went walks - least - when we were children we always went walks. We knew all the walks, where to go an
d - I don't - I know that - that - that - that my own children and my grandchildren, they're not interested - in the - in the - walks now like - well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You've got to go so far now before you get into the country to go for a decent walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Some of
 them are in the country. Oh - some of them are in the country. But we - now what - what - we used to - I don't know, we used to go round the Horse's Broth. That was where it was - maybe in the whole day. But we always went out. Then another day we would 
g
o away around the Kingholm. Now from - go there, and the Kingholm we liked that fine, maybe there'd be a boat in. At the New Quay, there might have been a - a - a boat in and - or something to see and then right up on and right over the Craigs and down th
at - that was a long walk though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would be a long walk for small children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Aye, well wouldna be so - so small then. But I don't suppose you'll ever have been there have you? Well you ken again you know a great walk if you went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Your husband was working for this other butcher at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He was on the van going round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
How did you manage for housekeeping in those days, were you fairly well off or did you have to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - you 
see - I - I didn't have to struggle because I was in - we'd always - often father said well of course - we'd always the roof. We'd always the - we'd no bother with - the house was always too big for us but - but we'd no - difficulties with money. I couldn
'
t because - I - I - you see, I've never been - difficult for - I never was - I've been thankful many a time that we were brought up with very little. That I know what it was to have very little. And I've never got away from that - sort of feeling, you kno
w
, I can remember - when we'd maybe just have - well - my father hadn't a big wage because - he was - although he was working with his father he was only getting a weekly wage. And - well my mother had so much of it and he - he said the first thing they do
 is put their rent and taxes was put past regularly every week, the rent and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 taxes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  was put past. And then - the rest was for housekeeping. But they never were - well off in these days. And even when my stepmother - I know that she wasna well off but - somet
imes - that the Saturday came - well she'd - pennies to count, you know, she was down to pennies. But then - we were well cared for and they came - but there were no doubt that the people we lived beside, they werena the same }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 calibre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 , they wouldna care whe
ther they had pennies or - what they had. Any - they were happy go lucky, at least I would think so. But - as I say, when we were little - it could be half a pound of stew or - or a - it could have been half a pound of something, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 three quarters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . But - I co
uld never say - there might have been - a pound of meat bought, but I couldnae say that ever I remember being sent for a pound, well - on a Saturday - what was a common thing was - getting - well - many time she would get a shillingsworth of pork. Now tha
t
'll be - might have been a pound and a half, and it would be roasted before the fire. It'd be a wee bit like this. And - she used to get - what we called the - the - side - it's a bit of the runner, it's runner now. It was the way it was cut then. And it 
w
ould be pot roasted, we'd have that for tea on a Sunday, now that could have been eightpence a pound so that was a shillingsworth. Sausage, I don't think she ever bought the butcher's sausage many time but - on a Saturday - my father would go to Lipton's,
 Saturday night, and maybe bring Lipton's sausages. They were a treat then. Of course - a lot of shopping was done on a Saturday in these days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That would be when the men were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - the men were paid in dinnertime. Saturday dinnertime. Th
ey were always paid Saturday dinnertime. But at - it was customary - of course that would come into the - when we get onto the town. If a - Saturday afternoon and - and evenings. Instead of of town being quiet it was busy. It was a busy place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Everybody was in doing their messages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Getting their messages and - and I know he used to go to Lipton's, maybe bring a pound of Lipton's sausages, well these in the bundles, they are something new. And we would have these and potato scone fried Sunday morning of course, that was a treat.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about when you got your own house to keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well of course I - I'd been keeping house from when I was sixteen year old. So that this continued and - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you do most of your shopping on a Saturday too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you - you'd always your grocery order on a Saturday. You always went for your groceries on a Saturday - sent up for your grocery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't actually carry the messages home yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, no, no. Oh no, oh all - all people - well m
ost people did that. They sent a list of their groceries and he sent them down. You've tea and sugar and all the things that you could think of was marked down. I remember - when Brasso came out first. Now - Wilson the grocer was in - where - next to - th
e chemist at the corner where it's a - a - beside Lipton's, it's - that - wee shop, well it was up steps then. And {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wilson{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 had a great big - quite a good business there. And - how they moved about - but they got through the business there. Now when Brasso ca
me out first he showed me this Brasso, and this - well of course he didna know - whether it would take, and he said, I had to buy thirty pounds worth - to get it - to get - to get it - with the discount they get - and - and - well that was a lot at that t
i
me for something entirely new. And I remember him telling me, he said, I had to buy thirty poundsworth. And he thought that was a lot. And Brasso or something - might not have sold. Previous to that you would get stuff in a wee - tin. And a wee sort of ti
n, Glo metal polishes and Matchless metal polish and - but this Brasso is a new thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And it took on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh it took on, oh yes, but - that was just the risk. But to think that thirty pounds worth at that time - for - for one wee article.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It's a lot for a small shopkeeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well it wasnae exactly a small shop but that was a lot of that one thing that might no have taken, to get - the most out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When you were buying food did you buy many tins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 There wasn't so very many - oh 
the tins now - oh - the place is swamped with tins and - oh no - no, salmon would be about then I think that you would get - and you got it in a tall tin and it wasnae very dear. Oh tinned salmon was quite an ordinary thing for folk to buy long ago. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would get most of your meat fresh with your husband being in the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 butcher}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Ah but - now he wouldn't become no butcher yet. Oh no a butcher. No, he was no a butcher until the first world - after the first world war. You see? No, we just bought our meat and - groceries and - and I got my husband's - wage and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
How did you work it out, did you know how much he was earning? And how much he was giving you for housekeeping and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Of course I did. Most wives did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I thought there were quite a few who just got so much in their hand every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well they maybe now but long ago the done things was - well I think most - wives would know what their husbands were getting, I don't think there'd be so many - 
the custom was long ago that the mother was the - purse bearer and - if she was a good mother. And she would - save and - and - and even where there's families in the house I don't think - it's a recent - of recent date I think that families began to boar
d
 with their mothers. Oh I think so. And I'm quite sure that long ago when - families we lived among and they were - in the - working in the mills and that - that their - their wages would go into the house - I may be wrong, but - I think the mother would 
- a good mother would disperse the money. I think so in these days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you were the one that had charge of the housekeeping purse then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - and you know I never - I never got into debt or I never remember being - I'd never no money worries. Never no money worries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Then once you were down here you would have the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I was - I was always here, I was always here. I never went away from here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
What size of house is this, it would be quite a big house for a young girl to look after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
It was far too big - yes, there's four bedrooms up the stairs. It was a nice house and a good house when we came to it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Are there four rooms downstairs as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Oh it's a big place. It was too big for a - for a girl th
at had no experience. But - and of course it was - in grandfather's time - well it - there were a lot of carpets in it, and - but there were - no the kind of carpets you get now. And - but my father shifted all the carpets and put down linoleum. So that w
a
s easy kept, but again - it had to be kept. There was nae polishing then, it was completely - always washing the floor. Oh you just had to wash the floor. And with - well - in a tenement house where we'd come from - generally the house would just be tidie
d
 in Friday and Saturday was the cleaning up days for Sunday. Well we used to - I think it would be morning - maybe Saturday morning that mother would - would - have a final clean up. But as - but - once - we'd all learned to work with her, but I'd learnt 
i
t well, we just had wood bottomed chairs and they were always done out on a - on a Saturday, you know. Just plain square chairs. And they were always wiped over before the floor was done. Also - the - the brush handles were washed, you know, it was a wee 
b
it - they were - don't see these wee brushes now. A wee brush with a handle - and they stood like that, called it a hearth brush. But it was - a wee - a - a head like that, and a handle up in the middle. Through the middle, well that was - that was all th
e
 kind of brush she had. And that was always - wiped before the - floor - was washed and - these sort of things. Now - and - oh - a good number of years ago, reverting from the story, but - but I went down myself one Sunday afternoon maybe - I might be twe
nty years, I - I've nae a - a recollection now of time, but I go down this nice Sunday myself to the quay, and I was just walking along. And - there was two ladies sitting - one I knew and the other I didn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was there a kitchen range or something
 that had to be cleaned at the same time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, had a great big range here. You had to - clean the flues, you'd a brush - clean the flues.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you do that once a week or every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, no, every Friday, a Friday I think. Now it was righ
t up here - and - and I - and it was - what they called - - it wasnae a closed range, you could close it and you could open it, but it was mostly open. But - it was right fire-eater, a right }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 coal eater}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . If you wasnae careful. Well of course coals were chea
p in these days. And you'd shovel and shovel of coals in. Well of course with - a careful person would have studied that fire but - you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 shovelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  the coals in and - well you'd to sweep all out the flues down and the soot - and - the - then you'd all this s
oot to rake out and - put into the bucket. And then you had to - all to blacklead. With a blacklead brush and - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 steel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  to polish. Oh you've - you've no idea - you don't know what - what you're - you don't know what you've missed. With the result that I 
used to be blacklead - pretty well blacklead my face and hands. And it was that - wee - latterly you got better blacklead but long ago - it was a wee sort of thing and you put it in water in a dish and - put water on it and then you'd - have a cloth and y
ou went over all this, then you had it all to shine off with a brush. Oh it was a - it was a right labour that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It would be a mornings work really to clean it all would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well it took a long time. It took a long time. To do that. And then you'd
 a fender with - steel fender and fire irons, all that to clean with - with emery paper. Oh you didnna ken what you've missed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 be glad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  when Brasso came then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh but the Brasso - the Brasso didnae take - but - you'd be glad - we'd be gla
d to - make better blacklead. And you began to know how to use it and then it - it - they made blacklead that didnae - you see, the blacklead you got - it went on but it came off in dust again. But - they began to - to improve on these things and you coul
d blacklead your grate only once in a while and - and - learn to keep it. You could keep it with this stuff. But it - it was still pretty hard work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you had a bathroom here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 We'd always a bathroom. I think this - I think this would be about t
he only house - here that had the bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have a hot water supply to the bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh it was right - oh yes, oh you'd any amount of hot - there was - the only thing is now - I've a very poor water supply simply - because - this - the -
 the pipe that was put in would be put in to serve this house. And - that - the - the - and so many taps would come off it. There's so many people at the first want it - and - there's - I've none - a fortnight ago I had none - at the - this garage in here
 had left a tap running and I'd no water.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But in the early days it was fine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh we had a - a grand supply, but not now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your grandfather or your great-grandfather or somebody build this house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, my grandfather built it - I woul
d think about - I would think about 18 - 60 something. I know it was here in 1869 because - on the door - one of the doors there's a painter has - a name and a date - a date so that it - a painter had been in it at '69. Once when I was washing one of the 
r
oom doors - and at the top there this man has - has - he's written his name, which was a common thing, and the date on the door, so - but - grandfather built the house in front first, that big house in front. And then he found it was too big. And he - he 
s
old - that one. He built this one down here and sold that one. You see. And he - came down here to live. But you see he'd only - I think he - his wife only lived twenty years so that he hadn't long. And then - there was no gas house - immediately here. Th
e gas house was in Shakespeare Street then. And it was a - a very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you do the washing at home too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When you were married here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No - we'd do so much but we always had somebody to come in and do the wash. It was kind of done thi
ng where there was a family. That - you got a woman to come in and do your wash. Well - maybe no everybody but - but I've done the washing was - maybe about fifteen years old I was up in the morning about - before five o'clock in the morning when - before
 we came here to do the washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But you had somebody to give you a hand after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh here, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When the children were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
When you were living here with your husband and your children did you do any of the decorating yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. There - there's not so many people did decorating then. No, generally they got a painter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When the children were small did they help you in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, they werenae put to work the same as what I had bee
n. No, no. They used to get up and get to - get to school, oh no. Oh no, they never I they never had - they'd never certain jobs to do. When I was small we had jobs to do. But not they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you not get the boys to bring the coal in for you and that kind of thing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well there's one still brings the coal in yet. But - but he never - he just brought it in. Now the other any - well granny lived at - down the road a bit, the - the other one, he would go in and sit and talk to granny for long enough and
 her fire could go down, he never saw the fire go down. The other one, he came into - he'd never much to say to granny but if he saw her coalbucket empty - he just went and filled the coalbucket. And departed. But if he saw granny had the - had the loan o
f
 something that belonged to us - he took it home. You see. He - he - well he knew it had to go but he saw it and - it went home, back home again. But it's the same yet. That - he's the only one that sees the coalbucket empty. The other one never sees the 
coalbucket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 When they were wee did you have a set time for putting them to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. Oh they used to get the bag of coals - up the stair - bag of coals going to bed, you know, this - and the gag - bag of coals up the stair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did your husband help you with them, did he take them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - he wasnae always here, he worked late. He was late - late coming in at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So you humped them up yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes, it was great fun. A bag of coals - bags of coal going up the stair.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You had a bathroom there, did they get a bath once a night or was it once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, I thin that they - mostly - at - once a week anyway. No, they didnae get a bath every night. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bath{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - once a week. Maybe if their feet was dirty they'd maybe be in the sink - in the back kitchen, the sink, wash their feet. But - I notice my son's wife, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 Sheila
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
, her kids is bathed - I didnae disagree with - the bath every night maybe is right enough but - but - in the summertime, but I don't think so in the wintertime but - that's no my business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How often did they have a change of clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Every week, every week and they'd always nightshirts or night - nightgowns and - but they were - clean clothes every week. Again - children - well children were differen
tly dressed then. They had more clothes. They wore combinations and then semmits and - and drawers or combinations. But there's no such a thing now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
