But it was Just Christmas and New Year and so on, it wasn't sort of every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, there may have been and odd Sunday but - but it was just a - an odd Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you cook on the range here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. M
y - we did get a gas cooker - but - that was for summertime. We used the gas cooker in summertime. Of course you'd always to have the range on for hot water. But - only - could cook - cook quite well on the range. You see, you could close it up and you'd 
a - it was a grand oven. It was a good - it was a splendid range and if you were careful - you could do all your cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you do much baking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I never - I didnae do a - canna say I was a great baker. No, no - now where would I get the time to bake? For parties - oh yes, for the - but we never were high livers. You know, we didna }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 buy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 a lot of cakes, we were - the - scones - there might have been scones but - but we didn't eat a lot of cakes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You kept them for special occasions too did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. For a birthday well I would have a great big - baking for a birthday party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you give the boys birthday parties regularly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh they - they'd all birthdays parties 'til they're twelve, but I don't think we ever had any thirteen birt
hday parties. They were twelve. And then, by that time - the last time that a birthday party was before we opened the shop, of course that's coming away to - by this time now - we're coming time here that - the war - the first world war came on. Now - tha
t }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 intervened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
. The first world war came on - it came on in - '14. Yes, '14. Isabel was born in May '14. And that August I think was when the war came on, was it August. I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you find that the war made much difference to you here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh wel
l - the - it didn't - it made a great deal of difference because - well my husband, he was still on his van then of course the - the men were conscripted. His age group of - I can't remember how they were taken up, but - he - he was taken for Army service
, now he wasnae a fit man by any means. By no means - a fit man. And he was put in a Labour Corps. And - well - he went - well then with what - there was Army pay then. Got Army pay then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Which would be less than he had been getting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I've no idea
 what I got. I haven't a - I haven't a clue what we got. But - we'd Army pay. Now that'd be about - I think it'd be 1916 that he would go to - he went to the - the K.O.S.B's and I think he was in - Edinburgh - at Portobello, he was stationed at Portobello
. Now I went there for a holiday, while he was there, and had a week in Portobello. The two - three children and I. And - then he was sent to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And he was in a Labour Corps. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} but - they werena very particular where they would go, they just - 
they just put them up the line, they were just - wherever they were sent. But he was anything but a fit man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How was he after he came back then? Had it affected his health?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - not greatly but - he - well when he came back from the Army he'd 
no job to come to. 'Cos his employer couldnae - had no work for him you see. He - that again's another story. The men that came back - the last war, their bosses had to take them back. And they were - and the families were looked after. But - we only got 
-
 we were Army pay, in the first world war, and find your own job when you come back. Now - I can remember a woman coming to the back door. Oh they're about the town, there are remains of them yet, and she'd a baby and she - of course she would have been -
 
at the door before but - she was begging. And - and her husband was in the Army and - and she had a - a dress for a baby and a - something else and - and she says she gets Army pay. Well I says, how do you think my - my - I'm getting the same pay as you. 
She was coming to beg from me, getting the same pay as what I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And you had a big house to keep up as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
But - there was just this - just the set up. And she was just - go around mooching.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You were saying you used to make a lot of jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes, made all - all the different kinds of jam as the season came on.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you go out and collect the fruits yourself for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You bought fruit, fruit was cheaper then, you bought - well rhubarb - well you made rhubarb jam, we had rhuba
rb - you made rhubarb jam and - strawberry jam. Gooseberries - black - made all kinds of jam because you went through a lot of jam. We'd always made - our own jam. Well we never bought jam, we just always made it. And you made it much cheaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you ever make marmalade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Only made one - marmalade in my father's time once because I hadn't a proper recipe but of course - I did learn to make - in later days to make marmalade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you also make any pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I think the only thing I e
ver - ever put in vinegar would be beetroot. Long ago, my stepmother, she used to make pickles, cauliflower and that, but then see it was grown in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 garden}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 have a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  really big garden here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And we - we'd no - nothing of that kind here
, and again - we werena pickle people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you ever bottle fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh it was a great - craze for a while, before this war - maybe during the war too - we used to - bottle - I bottled lots of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That's the 1939-45 war is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't do it in the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No - not that I remember. Oh no, I didn't do it the first world war but I may - I think I would bottle fruit - after that, we used to - I bottled a lot of fruit, quite a lot. And in these days I used to - 
do the marmalade, instead of finishing it off I would cut it up and - and bottle it and then - you could make a bun and - you know, you could - add the sugar and bring it up and - and finish it off. And - I did that once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You told me before about maki
ng botanic beer, you didn't ever try winemaking did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. No, the only - ever - the only thing I ever tried was this treacle beer. Quite a lot of wee shops used to sell it. Well they didna call it beer, they called it yill
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That's ale isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Aye. Aye. Teacle yill. It was quite common. I - I think so, I canna mind much about it but Eastertime they - it was the summertime they made that, treacle will. But quite a lot of folks make the botanic beer and I liked the botanic beer, it's quit
e good. Oh I like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you ever keep any pets in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You never had cats or dogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh we used to of course - we have - have cats. A cat. In fact - Mr Ascot, you know Mr Ascot, Jimmy Ascot, his got - a cat that's nineteen
 years old, he's got it - he got it from me. I'd like to see that cat, it' was the last cat that - that - we had a cat and always every litter she'd always have - a - a golden - what was it they called that - kind of line coloured one. A ginger cat. She'd
 always a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 ginger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 cat amongst the tribe, so - I was needing a home for this ginger cat. And I advertised it and Jimmy - Jimmy's cat had died so his wife needed a new cat so he got ginger, Jimmy got the ginger cat. And - I believe - I - oh it was only the oth
er day - the other day I come across this bit of poetry and it's nineteenth birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you very fussy about your children's table manners and things like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh you only - oh - you tried to keep - to keep them - yes. Oh yes. You tried to -
 you wanted your children to - to always to do what was right. I'd always a great interest in my children that they would never tell me a lie. Never. Whatever there was, always to tell me the truth. I - I dreaded - because I knew that - we used to tell li
e
s. To save your skin. And that was the one thing that I - ever hoped they would never tell me lies. There fore, I used to take - I used to listen to all they said, and - nothing - I never condemned them as long as I got the truth. They were never punished
 
for anything they did - of course if I thought they were doing something that - that they shouldna be doing then they got - well, they - they got the worst of the slipper. But - I never had a great deal of - of bother. But - that was the one thing. I was 
a
lways - hoped they would never ever tell me a lie. Because - well - this is a true saying, you can lock from a thief but from a liar you can't. but I - it was because I was dread that they would ever do what I did, tell lies. Therefore I took all ways and
 
means and I never nae difficulty in finding out the boys. They were easy to detect, the boys. You know, if they - if they - if they'd done anything - oh - they were - it was easy to detect them because - you told them off about it but - but - with Isabel,
 
it wasnae so easy with the lassie I don't know whether I've - and I used to - think - why else - I could sort of - to myself how I would find out things. As I say I had never much difficulty with the boys, finding out who - what - who did what. But - I co
uld remember - I sable, she might have been about three. And we'd occasion to go to a wedding. And - just - this room was smaller, it was - with the - the room being extended }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 upstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 , it occurred to me one day a number of years ago that we could extend out
 the nursery and make a good big living room. I was myself, by this time I was living by myself. So that that room from there, up and the new window has been put in. Otherwise it was just an ordinary kitchen window. Well my brother - I had - he was living
 
at the time - here at the time and we were going to a wedding in this afternoon. And - before he was the last that went out and shut the - and he turned back and threw a bag of sweeties onto the kitchen table which was just at the kitchen window, onto the
 
kitchen table and - before how went out. However when we come - later on in the night he says, where did you put the sweeties that was on the kitchen table? I said, I never saw sweeties. Oh, he said, so he just described how he'd thrown the bag of sweetie
s
. It all went quiet, nobody knew anything about the sweeties. But - knowing my brother, well - he - he - he wouldn't - I knew he didnae - so well - it would stick in his gullet if couldna find out where the sweeties had gone. So I tried all means of - thi
nk - ways and means to get the sweeties. I couldnae detect it. Couldnae - it was all open to - it lay within my fear, I knew,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804  I was sure. So - as I say, Isa}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 bel, she'd only be three, and the three were all in one bed. So - I put them to bed and - I said good
night, and of course that was something new, me saying goodnight to them. And she said - oh, she said, oh I'm no going to bed tonight. I thought and thought how I could find out. Oh, she says, I can't go to bed tonight. There's a robber in this quarter. I
 
said, coulna possibly go to bed. Because, I says, there's a robber, I says, took uncle - Uncle Jimmy's sweeties, so I said, I'll have to sit up and watch for this robber coming and he'll come again. Mummy, it was me that took the sweeties. This was Isabel
.
 She just pushed up the kitchen window and put her hand in and got the bag of sweeties. This wee voice, mummy, it was me that took the sweeties. All the time she'd - nobody knew anything about the sweeties I was that determined. And I thought, now there's
 
- that's - that was the plan it took to find out. Sit up and watch for the robber. So - of course - I would be that glad that - that - I don't know whether - whether it was a lesson to her always to tell the truth, I don't really remember, but - but it wo
rked. It worked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you smack them much if they got in bother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh they'd get their share of - but did you ever hear of a kid that not got a wee smack - for you know just some devilment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How did your husband feel about smacking them and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He never - he never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He didn't do any of that at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had to do it all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well I did it because - he wasnae much here you see he was out all day.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Then they would be gone to bed by the time he got back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would he see them at breakfast time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
He would be out - he would be out - he was out at seven every morning, with his breakfast, his breakfast and out at seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would get up first and give him his breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. Oh
 I - oh I - oh I was up and - get the fire on, get the breakfast ready and we'd eat breakfast and then the children would get up and get theirs for way to school. He was out for seven every morning with his breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did he come back for his dinner or was he away all day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you see that - he - he would - no, he came back for his dinner but any - he had nae regular - they werent nae right hours. And - back when he would get the chance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have a cooked breakfast for him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Y
es. I can't remember. Well you see - he couldna - you can't begin with porridge because if he'd porridge well he can't eat much after it and porridge doesn't last long. But he would have a cooked breakfast possibly bacon and egg or - bacon and sausage or 
some - bit - but there's no - we don't have cooked breakfast now but in these days - he needed something substantial.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Would the children have a cooked breakfast before they went out to school too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh I think so. I think - oh I think they got porr
idge. As far as I can remember. When - when he came back from - from the work - from the war well then - there was no work for him to come back to. And - he got so much money given - you'd so much money, and then - you'd to go before a board to - say why 
you werena working and - well he couldnae get work. And - he - well I decided - I had it in my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 mind}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  that - there was nothing to hinder him to start work on his own. Of course the thing was - he couldnae get - supplies, he couldnae - he couldnae get - meat, 
to cart, like to start up with. Well - he'd gone before this board this time and he'd said if he could get an allocation of meat - he could earn his living, with take up his job and his van, that they had - that they had - worked with his - boss before. T
h
e boss couldnae employ him, but he could take up his van - and start out his van again and - well so he did, and he'd no bother selling. 'Cos all the people knew him and he was well liked. He'd go into his old rounds near and he was - you know, he was wel
l liked in his old rounds and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did his old employer not object to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. He helped - he - he said he would help him all he could, which was - offered to buy his meat. No. Oh no, he said, of course - and - and again he couldnae get off the Arm
y until he got work. They wouldn't release him. Now - they wouldna release him. Now why was that? They wouldna release him. Well I saw his boss, and I said to him that - that - he could claim him back, I said to him - that - I was thinking that Willie cou
l
d start on his own. Now - he says, well - he said, any help, he could - he could - ask for his release but - he hadnae the work for him. So he said, if I cared, and he did, he applied for a - for his release, to get home to work. And - and - and he said t
h
at - he would give him any help he needed. Help him what he could. And he did. Help him to - he bought stuff for him and - and - and - that's how he started his business. He went round with a - with what stuff he got and he could - no bother to sell it. W
e
ll - the children were getting up by this time and we took that shop up there where they are now. And in due course I went into the shop, well we'd no trade - you just had to wait. Well I knew nothing but I was keen enough and anxious enough and did my be
s
t - to help him. And - you know - I was just out to help my husband in every way. And - that was how we started. I used to count it dinnertime to see how much in the drawer and maybe about six shilling or - and it gradually mounted up until - we saw that 
we could keep a man. Once we saw that we could - have enough work for a man, we got the man. And the man we got was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 boxes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  son. His own boss had to clear out of the shop he was in. There - fore his son - was out of a job. And - his son Tom came and worked to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you carry on working after you got the man in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 A wee while. A wee while and then Tom - worked away himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But you've always done the books all the way through?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well I did a lot of the - the - you see, it was difficult w
ith my husband being away - all day, well - any - there - there were very little booking to do then because we'd made up our minds it - it was to be cash trade. You see? You couldnae afford to give - it's difficult - it's no so difficult now for the local
 
- the supermarket, there'll be nae - there'll be nae booking at the supermarket. But - we made up our mind, well I got advice from people in shops that - never give credit. Just say no. And - it's been weekly, it's monthly now some but it was - weekly, an
ybody, it had to be weekly. But mostly cash over the counter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was it a horsedrawn van that you had to start off with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Where did you keep the horse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - various places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Down here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, various place - various stables.
 Of course he'd always - there was always a horse - a horse and van that he had - with his old boss. There was always a horse for him. And - oh he's had queer horses. And queer vans. And - well when he went away to the Army first - his old boss had - had 
a
nother man on the van. And - at that time they were keeping a horse down here. So - his old boss, the arrangement was - he had so - like when - when he - he worked with his old boss, the arrangement was - he'd so much wage and his meat. You see, because t
h
e boss wasn't working in the shop, he was depending on his men. So he - he said he'd be better to let them take their meat - than they'd take it. So he allowed them to take their meat. Well at that time, with me living with my father here - we let - we di
d
na take the meat. Granny got the meat. Well - he couldn't expect a - a - him to supply meat to - to this household when there was a - a family here. So we agreed that granny could get the meat. She lived further away. That she would get the meat. That he 
- was - he was due. So she got the meat. So after he went away - to the Army, well - the horse was down here, well I used to - get the horse ready for a long time, keep it - have it ready for the boy coming up for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you groom it and feed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I would feed it - feed it and - oh I could do that in these days and - harness it and have it ready, standing ready for the boy to - to collect and - and - at this time, because - it was generally the last minute they came. So that I - I would get u
p in the morning and feed the horse and then - and then - then put its - put its clothes on. Harness it and have it ready for the boy coming. So that was in lieu for - still the meat we were - still - granny was still getting the bit meat. We just felt th
at was - well it gave you that wee bit of - you werena taking it for nothing. I would let you see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
So you've always had something to do with the business, you've always been quite close to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Always. I was always very close to it. I might say I
 was - in the earlier days when we were - we - we just - start with - I was - I interest and of course - with being - interested I never was out in business in my life, I never was anywhere out of here, and with having the interest in my father's business
 and that kind well it gave you an interest in it for your own, it was - although it was a butcher's business well you'd to work for it and to make the best of it. That - I was - as I say enterprising. I was always gae enterprising. I would -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had the ideas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, I - I - yes, well - well - he was - more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804 timorous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 , you know, but I - I wanted him}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804  to get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 on, to - to - and spurred him like. No that he needed spurring with the work, he was a grand worker, he would work from morning to night, but - b
ut I - but I concocted ideas and - and - well I made potted meat and I - I did - everything I could to help. Now you buy that big black pudding, do you ever buy black puddings, and slice it. Well - I would be - the first in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} that made that black pudding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It's a kind of messy business isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, mess - black puddings the best when it's just new made, but - and you - you - they slice it now. Well used to always to get wee round ones. Well - at this period - the man in the shop was - wa
s off - I forget what was wrong with his thumb but - but I was making the black puddings. And - this old shop that - we - got skins from and the man came, I said to him - I says could - I'd the idea - well I could make haggis, and I could make the black p
u
ddings. Well I had the idea - the - the wee - you have a week round, it was a pest, you had wee slices. You see. You put them in the pan you - you had wee slices to turn over. And I had the idea how much - that it would sell - a sliced black pudding that 
t
hey could get maybe two or three slices, and they had a wee bit that was tasty. A black pudding's tasty if it's a good black pudding. I like a black pudding. And - I said well, I'm quite sure that would sell, if it was made in that - a long one, yes, and 
slice it down, you see. So I asked this - could he make - get me a skin. So - at that time he had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 cleaned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  the skins in the market. So he - he supplied me with the skins. And it sold right away with no bother. The - the black - the sliced black pudding went.
 And - now I was the only one that was making them. Now that would be - oh it took me a while to think how many years back that's since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Probably not very long after the shop started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. I couldn't exactly say when. But - that was how it starte
d. And it was my idea. The sliced black pudding. And he'd nae bother - and he - now all he charged me was - a ha'penny a time for the - the skin. 'f course that was buckshee to him because - there would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 nobody}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  be using this skin and he brought me this - th
ese skins down and - and - then the rest must have copied. You can get it anywhere now. You can get it anywhere. But - I don't like the skin it's in. The skin it - it's in - sticks to the - you've to chew it, you canna get the skin off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I think they use plastic nowadays don't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No, but - and - and can you get the plastic skin off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You can peel it off before you fry it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Aye, because if you fry it with the skin on you canna eat it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You made other things for the shop too then, you said you made potted meat?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. I made potted meat, and - and - I would make the haggis. Although I - I could make the haggis. Of course I could make haggis before I went to the shop, because my mother could make haggis. But making haggis - for yo
ur house and making for a shop's a different thing. You'd to make in bigger quantity. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would you just make it down in the house here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I used to make the potted meat here, for a while, and then it was made up in the shop. And haggis' I 
made the shop. But - I was quite - I was quite pleased that - we'd - with the black pudding. It - that was my own idea because I thought - that - they could buy a half a pound of black puddings if they wanted - they are - it was a nuisance, these - tiny -
 turning the wee bits of - of pudding over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
If somebody was on their own and just wanted a slice for their tea they could get it?
