\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes. Ye
s, but there was no - none - in each other's houses. Some of them did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 Oh some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  of them were never - couldnae get their work done, they were just - loitering about - an awful lot. I don't think it's quite so bad now the - see, but the more in self contained
 houses now, of course I don't know what goes on - in housing schemes now. But again when we came up here, well I had no neighbours here you see. Except the people at the back. And well - you're too far away - I could be here - a week and no see anybody. 
You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Your father and stepmother didn't associate with other people that were in the same sort of job as themselves, the same }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 sort of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, just - like the - they - they were neighbourly, they - well they - they were just - it's different, people are different now but - they - my father didnae take up with them, well he - he hadnae much time. But there was no - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 you know, coming into your tea or anything, going - nothing of that kind and - and I don't think the neighbours do - in
 - in these days. 'Cos the womenfolks that - that - did the loitering, a lot of them. But - my father never did. For one thing he had nae time, he was out early in the morning and he came in at night, and he just came in and he was in his house, and then 
h
e had an allotment, and that took up his time so that that there wasnae time for - and then there was some of the - the neighbours, they didna bother with allotments or anything of that kind, they were just - they - was - was some quite nice, others were 
a wee bit - careless. You know, clattered away at the doors. Clashed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Who would you say were considered the important people in the district then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well I think - there were more or less - all - some of them had better jobs, there was - now in the
se days men that worked in a - an engine driver was considered - he would have good pay. An engine driver in these days. They would have good pays and then there was printers, there was - some worked about the mill and - and - then another - there was ano
t
her lot in a building opposite, it's away now, well they were well you'd call - you'd here - they're here today and away tomorrow. You know, they - they could do a moonlight flit. They'd really only one room in that building, it was a great big building. 
And - they'd be there, and they were just all kinds in that building, they were just a wee bit - some of them no very - you didnae bother much with them, some of them were quite tidy decent folks but - they were just a general - mixture of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 These were the ones that you weren't allowed to play with the children?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - they were scruffy sort of. They were scruffy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were they sort of looked up to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, you know, the shops in St Michaels
 Street, they made money, because you see - as I said before - the most of the people would be working, the majority would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 mill workers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 . Least - there was a big lot of mill workers, lived about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wallace Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. There were all kinds in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Wallace Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But
 St Michaels Street and - and - well - there was the - one, two - there - well you see one became Provost, he had been in the mill, and he'd been a foreman in the mill, and he'd be Provost McCall and became Provost in - in Dumfries. And - I think he would
 
be - been about thrice married. Well, he started a wee shop. So he got - he got notice that - well - and then he'd been a foreman in the mill. So that - any - he was a foreman in the mill, so - if he had some - his workers that dealt with him in his shop,
 
he could - maybe give them a privilege - I don't know what, but he got notice that if - they must have complained - some of the folks that werenae dealing with him would notice that some dealt with him got a privilege that they didna get, I don't know, bu
t
 that went - I think that would be right enough, and he was notified that if he was going to be a shopkeeper he would have to leave the mill. He could either - keep his job in the mill or leave the mill and become a shop, so - he left - he left - the mill
.
 And another old person beside him, he - whether - whether he got the same notice or no but he certainly had been in the mill too, but they - made - made a good - a good wee living in these wee - huckster shops they called them, sold everything, scones an
d
 - and then further along there was a licensed grocers shop. Of course it's away now, but - and he did a good trade. Of course he'd a license. It was the - I think it - I don't exactly know what - all he would sell but I know that - that the wee bottle, n
o
w - to give you an instance - my father was a strict teetotaler. Well, there was a - a person lived in Park Terrace, and - she used to send them to - to - to the grocers with this - I don't know whether she had it in a bag you know but she sent with the g
r
ocers and they went to the grocers, and it was for whisky. Of course she could get a gill of whisky you see. So he'd been away a message for - for Mrs Glendinning and he would get a ha'penny for going the message for her, a gill of whisky. So my father ha
d
 got them this day and - naturally had been - so he wrote a note to the husband and - said that he - I don't know what he said but he - told sent around to the husband that - his boy wasna to be sent for - for - well whatever it was. You see? So - I can r
emember that much. So - but he wasnae to - to go for it anymore. So he was never asked to go again. But, well - it wasna a nice thing to do, send a child. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Your father being in the family business like that, do you think he'd feel he was on the same level as a shopkeeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well - again - again, now tradesmen and shopkeepers are a different lot altogether. No, and - and there was another - grocer along the road, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Brampton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, he'd a grand business. He - he had - at the top of Swan's Vennel, he had
 quite a good business. No, you canna class - class the tradesmen and the shopkeepers - their no the same class. They're no - they're no in the same - income group. It's difficult to define.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Who do you think would be better off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well - these we
e shops - the higher up the street would have the better - some of these - the shops - further up the street, but these - wee shops - made - they would make money and they would lose a lot of money too because - there was - there was - there was days and 
that - that time of life when there was no work there was no pay. So that people dealing with these wee shops would need to get - credit sometimes, and it's a question if ever repaid it all back. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And some of the mill workers were here today and gone tomorrow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - oh no, no, that would - that was - but that happened with all trades, all workers in trades, maybe these - some of these people that lived round about - they would maybe - might have been - masons or labourers or - but - and t
here was - there was no work there was no pay in these days. Except a man was - well - I don't know, there'd be some jobs you'd get a - a standard pay, but where the man was paid for by the hour, if there was no work - there was weather - they couldna wor
k, well there was no pay. So they just - it was an existence. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 So that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  they need to get credit from some of these wee shops where they dealt, and pay back when their - when the work, started again. So it's questionable if ever these wee shops got - everythin
g that they were due. Well I know - now - my father would have slaters worked with him and - and I know this - wee grocer down in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St Michaels Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, she - notified him that - they were owing her money. So he did deduct a little, I think he did, but I'm no
t quite sure on that, of his weekly wage. I canna just mind but she appealed to him that she - he had - he'd had credit when he wasna working, and - of course they had to - she was due to get - repaid. But that was what happened in these days. So that if 
- there'd be a lot of wee shops that wouldnae - they wouldnae get back what they'd - they wouldnae get their - they wouldna get all their bad debts back. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about ministers, teachers, doctors, people like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 The minister didna know you. O
h the minister these days he didna know you. When the minister came to visit you sat in the back and - and you just - made his annual visit, you just - come in and - and talked, what it would be, sat there like a lot of stookies, the ministers in. No, I'm
 
afraid - that Doctor Patten wasnae a - and I think on - on the - the - walking along St Michaels - I can see the - people of importance, walking on St Michaels Street, and Doctor Patten was one. And he was just walk down. And instead of the minister - may
b
e - not - knowing the people that he passed - he just - he was just the opposite you know. Well - of course I was a lassie then, I don't know what he would do but - the minister didn't know you in the street. And I don't think - and I canna remember the m
inister ever speaking to you any time. No in these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You say you can visualize the important people walking down the street?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, I can see - Thomas Watson the Standard. Now he was a great -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would he be the editor of the Standard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, he was. Well, he was - he was a great man. You see, the Standard, it was a - a real - paper, you got all the - news in it, you could - it was a - that one paper has been a great miss - the Standard. He would - now who would be editor - well, Jim Dic
key was editor with him too, and - he - but Thomas Watson, you see he brought up the - the McDowall's History of Dumfries, he wrote it up to date. With wee bits of his - that I - I can visualize meeting you see in the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about Doctors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were they looked up to a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, the doctors were - oh they were - they were class. Now my Sunday school teacher - was a Miss Murray. She - she made - of course they thought she - he wasnae good enough for her you see. Oh yes, the do
ctor's - I think the whole - I don't think they were all alike. Their own Doctor Smith, and - but the doctors - and they - they - they all wore all the tall hats and - and - you know, they were dressed, and Doctor Murray had a - he had a - what they calle
d a groom, he was - they'd all - they'd all a horse and - a coachman. Doctors in that days. The only one - was Doctor Carr, he started off on a bicycle. He was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 That was unusual for a doctor was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well he was a young fellow then, he was - he w
as - well he was the - you know, he was a smasher him. He was a fine looking man, Doctor Kerr. And his father before him had been a doctor. And he'd became - I think he would become assistant now - I don't know whether - where he came to work to doctor Fe
rgus, Doctor Fergus was never he never married. He was a sort of a - brought all the babies home, Doctor Feguson. He was well liked, Doctor Ferguson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 If you met the doctors in the street would you speak to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Ah well the doctor would ride his 
machine. Oh no, no. Oh no, the doctors were always in their carriage, oh no, you didn't speak.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would you ever have to curtsey to anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No. Oh no, nothing of that kind. Oh no, no, no, no, no, no so much as that. Oh no. No, no. No, there was nothing of that kind, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How about teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well you looked up to your teacher. All through the school. Yes, the teacher was respected. As soon as this - they did away with this strap business the - it deteriorated. There's none of the manners,
 there's not the manners, there's not the - the - you taught - you were mannerly in the school. And - no, there was no cheek. No, no, there was - there might have been an odd boy we could - you knew he was a bad boy. Of course he got more of the belt than
 the - but - there wasnae - there was manners and - and - you thought something of your teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But a teacher wouldn't be on the same level as a doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
They're a different class. The doctor'd be above the teacher I would think. I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about the sort of County people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 The gentry. Well there was nae gentry now. They're all away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would they be up above even the doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes, they'd - they'd be gentry. Oh aye, the gentry - and - and now - to be quite truthful, these people - well - if you begin to think like there are all kinds of animals, there's - there's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 thoroughbreds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 and there're just - the - the - but - but - but - no - but again - we must give it to them, that there was something in some of the gentry, breeding
, that wasna in the - you still get it. You can still - still see it. And the lower class of people, you see that - the - the lower class people that - that there are no breeding in, that they're just - but as you - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 you went}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  up higher that - there was this
 - they commanded respect. And there's nae getting away that people like - like animals had - pedigrees, you know, that - they - they're - they're coming from a pedigreed I would say people before them. And again there was the - the gentry as there would 
be gentry of course, there's still some of them about I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you tell me about any of these that you knew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well - no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Was it possible for people to move from a lower class to better themselves, for a labourer to get a better job and better himself do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well there may have been - there may - no, it wasn't so }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 not cable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 then, there may have been - there has been folks that have - moved just a little up - have been - they've had a wee bit more brains and got the sta
rt you see some people, they - if they didna get - couldna get the start - everybody gets a good start now. That everybody - everybody has an equal chance if they take it now, at the school. And they're guided. You see. Now - we just - leave - we've to le
ave the school, no matter what you were going to be. Now far up - even up to - Willie's class - there there was no - there were - there was no careers - affair for them, to be - guide a boy into what he was - what he could do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 He would just be left to find a job for himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes. Or - take his hire or do what they liked. You know, just - nobody bothered. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I suppose in a poorer family a boy would have to leave school whether he wanted to or not to bring in money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well you see my
 - that - well that was the case with my husband had to do that, he - he - he left when he would be eleven. He left when he was in the first standard, now - he would be - a question - he wouldna - I don't - he might have been twelve. But - he - he could l
e
ave in the fifth standard, he could leave in the school, he was nae fond of the school. Of course being brought up with a mother that was - having to - find the means, ways and means to bring up her family - he - well - they used to carry milk, now - they
'
d go for - there'd be milk boys and sell paper, anything to - to - to get extra, there was quite a lot of boys ran - carried - before they went to school in the morning carried milk round the doors, delivered milk. And they would only be get a shilling or
 
- something like that for it. Now, there was a family - lived up this street, there's three girls. And our milkman - came - after we came up here we got it from a milkman that came in from - Rigghead, now that's out beyond Collin. And this boy - he was su
p
posed to leave about - it was about three in the morning milking and he would be leave Rigghead at - after - about five o'clock or somewhere round about that, sell milk on the road in or deliver milk, the road in, from Rigghead. He would come in with his 
horse and cart. And these girls - he - he come to the Theatre Corner there, blew his whistle and - the - they come down the street and go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 to him and deliver milk. At seven in the morning. Well - that used to get me - you were sound asleep and they would - t
he milk would come. Well - and it was this - my father would say, there's the milk. And I had to get up and get this milk. Oh that was - and a cold winter morning and he - and - and he wouldna leave the cans. No, no. And - well - I didn't care - my father
 - but I had to get up and get the milk in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Do you remember anybody ever being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well, when you think on some of the folks - I don't know who the ladies would - I - I told you that I - we used to go up and play at the Home. Well there would be a committee of the ladies, they always called - they were always called the ladies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What sort of people were they then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well, I don't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Would it be your doctor's wife or the gentry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 She mi
ght have been. Well - you see - the - the ladies committee would be a - one of them was - a Miss Crichton, and she wasnae - only getting - no great importance. She collected - used to collect - money for nurse - the Jubilee nurses. There was the - the - t
h
e first of the - these - district nurses were two - nurses, the Jubilee nurses, the Queen's - Jubilee nurses, and they - they were - voluntary, and she used to collect - for the nurses. Well, she was - maybe somebody - she was no - nobody of any importanc
e but she would live in a better class of house in a better - better class district. But who Miss Crichton was I don't know. But she was one of the ladies that used to come up to the Home. Oh here's the ladies, and they scurried away, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 out in - out of sight, deary }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
It wasn't just the people with big houses and estates that did that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, I think it'd be a local committee, maybe doctor's wives or - or maybe a - a solicitors wives, some kind of - something like that. I think so. Now t
he - the doctors that I can remember, the oldest one was Cunningham. And he was a - an Irish doctor, and - he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Do you remember seeing a policeman round about where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes, if - if ever you saw the policeman you bolted. The - the boys.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Was he strict with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh yes. For no - for doing nothing. If ever the policeman - if ever the policeman - put his - an appearance, they hopped it out of sight. Kept out his road. Oh that was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Were you ever threatened with the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 If you had ever been naughty did your mother ever say she'd call a policeman?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no, oh no, the - you're mother didnae but neighbours did. Oh if the boys had maybe played football and - maybe the ball had hit somebody's window that would be enough. Now, in - when - we went to live in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Henry Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 first it was - it wasnae a made up street for a long time. And it was a - a - be a dirty place to play in, the boys used to play football in the street. And this neighbour, she was a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 house proud}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
 person and she - she gave them in of course a great deal of the boys were - names were taken and they were summoned to appear. So they went up to the police court, and - this bunch of boys - and it was the Chief Constable that did the - 
well he was the presiding Magistrate at this time. And he was Chief Constable Moltor. And - he was - he was an oldish man, and - he read out - he must have read out what they were charged with. So this boy, you know the boys he'd been - he was a wee bit-b
o
lder than the rest, the says to the - he says, what's he saying? Because they described after he couldna tell what he was saying because he said the saliva - the saliva was running down his - waistcoat, and old teeth was - reading this, and he says, what'
s he saying. They didn't know what he was saying. No. He was drool - drooling away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
I think - if - I don't know whether they were fined half a crown or no. I'm no sure. They werena ever - if there were any fine it was this - 
it was half a crown. They maybe didna get no fine, I can't remember. But there was no place for them to play, but the street. It was prohibited, playing on the street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 How do you think the policemen would treat the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Of course the policema
n then hadna very big pay. He'd maybe get a job as a policeman when he couldnae get a job as - much else. Oh no, the policeman - and he - and he was an authority, oh he would soon put them in their bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They were quite strict were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh aye. 
And - if they - they - they - they caught them doing something they - they could give them a cuff on the lug, oh they could - do as they liked with the kids }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9783127\charrsid10313804 
there.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about the grown ups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh well I - I couldnae tell you, I - how he got
 on with grown ups but - but you were left with the thought of the policeman - chasing boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you come in contact with the landlord much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No, no. No, no, you see, you only - paid your rent every six months.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They didn't come round every week and collect it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh no. Pay every - it was paid every six months. The first house we would be in would be nine pounds I think and - it wouldna be any more. It would be nine pound rent. Now when we went into this other house it had an extra bed
room, when we shifted into the new house and I think it was - it was ten pounds. A - a - ten pounds a year it would be. Be ten pound a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did-you know the landlord, did he live beside you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. He lived in Greenbrae, he was an engine driver. T
he landlord of - of the first house where we lived in they lived - because they lived in the - one block themselves. They lived there. And of course - they - they kept }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 your eye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  on - and if - if you'd some kid - other kids in - in the back green, she would 
rap on the window and get - had no - they'd no right to play in the - you couldna bring - other folks children round to play in your back green, she wouldn't allow that. Oh we kids, it - it was wrong. But - I never - we never - never remember playing much
 in the back green.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You would just play out in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 What about your engine driver landlord, you wouldn't see him so much then?

