\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Nothing like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. Oh there used to be od
d people that - boys used to pay plant with - play pranks on you see, you know - play tricks. A bit of thread, and they would - have a bit of thread and they would - this was a - just a - a boy's caper, play tick-tack. And would have a - it might have bee
n a bit of slate pencil or something and they would have the thread and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 fastened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  across a window, and then when they pulled the thread the - this pencil would rattle at the window you see. And this was done in the dark tick-tack. And it was tricks. No - no,
 I don't think there was anything. Of course there was they neighbours that - that - boys - that werena too friendly and of course they were - they got tricks played on them. There was the - that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It was just the children who did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Once you were settled into your house with your own family here did you keep up with any of the girls that you knew at school, did you have friends come in for tea or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No. I say we never - we - we - well I'd never been u
sed - well being a girl here, I'd never been used having - tea and - tea and people in the house there. But that - that - didn't seem to be done. Maybe - some folks would do it but - well I'd never been used with it. And - well what's a girl at - at sixte
en year old? Landed then to keep a house like this. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 But when you were married and had children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh I - well - well - no, now you see I told you - that I was married in 19 - Willie came in 1909, and that at 19 - the end of that year my father 
took ill, well I'd him to look after and then - into 1910 - that'd be 1910 my father took - took ill, Willie came 1909. And then that - into - at 1910, summer - that summer my father took ill. Well I had to - sort of keep his books and - and then - and - 
in 19 - 1911 I had him to look after, he was more or less an invalid. And he died in June so that - that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
How about when your husband was away during the war, did you have much company then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You didn't have any girlfriends then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
No, I never had girlfriend - I - I've more or less - a lone bird. Always. No - no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You had friends that you went to visit at Nithbank when you were small?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Yes, but - but they - I never - you see, you got out of touch with them, we got marrie
d, got out of touch with them. And the - maybe the two or three years that - that - that - after I was married I was out - got out of touch with them. You know like - like - I never was - they never came here. I never - well they - they - they would shift
 
their jobs, I didna ken what - but one thing - there was never a greener girl - before I was married than what I was. Well, I know that - that - I was acquainted with a - with the person that got the - where MacAuley's shop was. And - now the girls there,
 
now there was one girl there - I used to go to this wee shop. And - Dolly and I became very friendly. Well then she got friendly - she was - down about Arbigland. And she was a housemaid about Arbigland. And - she - got friendly - there was a gamekeeper t
here which you know - he and his wife - I learned later on but I didna think anything about it but - his wife had left him. Of course, I - and - and - a - a gentleman's estate's a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11935778\charrsid10313804 q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 ueer bit to - for folks to work. But this big family - there was - Arbigland
 House at that time kept up a full staff of servants, butlers - coahmen, footmen, the whole lot. Well she got the second housemaid's place there. In these kind of houses - they were particular who they took into their houses. She got second house - second
 
housemaid. Then - the first housemaid - had got friendly with the - the gamekeeper. Now whether it was that - but his wife had left him. And then - Dolly got friendly with him. But - but me - knowing nothing, I didn't think anything of it. Nothing - nothi
n
g about it. I don't know whether I told you that - I went down once - the - the - there was a bus run from Kirkbean to - the White Hart Hotel. And that was the mans of transport, like a - a public bus. It run twice a week, Wednesdays and Saturdays, and tr
a
nsport to that was the - the public conveyance, to Kirkbean, and then of course they would have to walk to - to - to - to Arbigland from Kirkbean. Well - Dolly - was coming up this day and I was to go - I went down to see her off on the bus. And - it was 
a
 very wet day. Well, I went down and - here - she was at the door, and she - the - custom was then to go into the pub's parlour in the hotel you see, the - the - the - a wet day they would go in there and wait for the bus - to be gathered up to the bus co
m
e up. So this day I went down - and - Dolly - immediately in - I was into - to - before I knew where I was I was in this pub. Amongst a lot - the rest, and - all the passengers waiting. And this gamekeeper was there. And before I knew where I was I had a 
g
lass of port wine in my hand. That was the drink then. Well I did - I felt rather uncomfortable. And I thought, if my father knew - if my father - was down and catches me here, he would have belted me up the Vennel. You know. I got - I drunk this - I didn
'
t know what to do, I drunk this stuff. Then of course - I had to come home. And I - I come out of that - hotel - thinking my father could be standing outside waiting as if he would - how worried I was. I said well I'll never - never, never do this again, 
I'll never be - led in like this again, if I just get out of this district -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It bothered your conscience?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - I was - taken unawares. But I never was in the same predicament again and I - I wasn't expecting such a thing you see. Well - that g
irl went on, she got very friendly with the - the gamekeeper. And - I didna think anything about it. Then she became ill and she was at home a good while. To make a long story short - she had a baby at home. I used to go down and keep her company, thinkin
g she wasna well. And so - she'd be sitting - doing a patchwork quilt. Well which was a nice handy thing for to sit and sew and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9572179\charrsid10313804 nobody}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804  - I wouldnae see anything wrong with her. Well - she had that baby. Now - it was years before I knew. And that would be sh
ortly - wee while before I was married - year or so before I was married. I'm not quite sure how long but - but she had that baby. Well - I knew nothing about it. And then she went away to another place, she got better. She was away to another place. Well
 
- in the course of time I was doing - down the shop one day and there was a couple come in and they had a baby, and they were nursing - you know, and the - this - at this time this - people's baby, which I thought was their baby - it would - might be six 
months old. And I - knew the people and - I just said how like his dad he was, you see. Well - that passed off. I thought it was their child. It wasnae their child, it was this girls. They had adopted it. It was before - years before I knew that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You could arrange adoptions like that quite easily couldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Themselves - oh they would agree to take it. It would just be adopted. Nae - nae bother about it, there'd be nae - nae nothing. I don't know, but - that child was - well - well then - now I
 never noticed that my girl chums - had - well - they thought I had known all about this. 'Cos I say it was years before - they spoke about it. And it was then - I said, I didn't know. And they - they - they - they were thinking that I'd known and was cov
ering it up and - and - never saying a word, never telling anything about - they knew, they knew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 It wasn't just that girls in general didn't know a lot about these things?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I didn't know but - no other - no, I didn't know. I didn't know. And they
 had heard this story, they would hear the story you see. They would hear all about it. Well you see I wasna living that - but - but they were - coming - going and coming amongst people that they would hear this story. Now - it was years before they told 
m
e - about this. Well, I says, I didn't know. And they thought I was keeping that dark. I didn't know one thing about it. And - of course the - the - the girls mother, she was just a fly - she was a very fly woman. I know that now, I didn't think so at the
 
time. And - here am I now - writing - some time ago - a - some of her family writing from - well I kept up contact with that person for a while. With the mother being - she gave up the shop and she went out to - to Greenbrae. But the time my father was il
l
 I seemed to have got out of - touch with her you see. And she got out of touch with me. Then - I couldnae get a nurse, when - when my next baby was coming and - I got her to come. And she came, and she was with me. She came. She could do that sort of thi
n
g. And she was with me. And - well the - we got kind of friendly, but no just close friends but were - that - as I say, I didnae - I wasna in the habit of - of going certain days to - to people or anything like that. However time went on and we - the frie
ndship - the friendship - dissolved, it - I got out of touch with her - altogether. I didna bother go near them. And - so some time ago I saw in the papers, and it was one of her - offspring - descendants from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and she was - wanting to get in touch
 with - her - thingummy's here. Well, she did get in touch with - some of the - of the relatives, but I thought to myself, I wonder what - who's daughter you are and I - so I replied there. I wrote to this person. So, here am I writing to this - to this -
 
grand-daughter of Beaton's Beaton was the old body's name. Here am I writing to this grand-daughter of the Beaton's now and she's writing to me quite nice letters and things. And she - she - Mrs Beaton had a - she had a - her eldest daughter - her eldest 
d
aughter - was - in a place, she was much older than me of course, she was working when I was a lassie. But - I don't think she come up to the scratch with her mother. And she went away, and I think as far as I remember she - she married a Pole who was a m
i
ner. She got up about the Lanarkshire district and she fell in - now there was a lot of Poles miners up there, in - in the pits at - at that time. There'll be descenders of Poles yet, but there was quite - and I think - he was - either if he wasnae a Pole
 he was - he was a miner anyway. This was her eldest. And this family - it's the eldest son of the eldest daughter's family. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did you have people to play with when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Well, you see, my mother - stepmother, well she had bee
n - she had been - a farmer' daughter and the farmers in these days they were - they werena very well off, they were poor, and it was customary for the girls to go to places or work on the farm, work at the farm - and if there was boys, they were anxious 
f
or the boys - to be - to get a - to get the education. It was - to get - they could - manage enough to get a boy a minister or a - into - something - other than - than a farmer. If they could get their boys - and the - the women, the girls - their wages c
a
me home to the mother and she dispersed the wages and - - and - and - and - that was the thing then for - for they were anxious for their sons to get on. They got the chance. And - now what was I going to lead into? Aye well, she - they would - they would
 be - Come home from the school, and - they would have work to do - you see. But she didna approve of the playing very much. No, were never much play in my life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Can you remember any games that you used to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 They played far more games than th
ey do now. All the games - that - now - in later years I got Kerrs singing games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
After you were married and you were living here you had your younger brothers here too had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 I lived here with - the three brothers stayed here. You see? And - 
they - well the eldest brother went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose} - he went away to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}, he was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And he came back from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, he got married and then - the next one stayed with me here until he got married. He got married after the first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 And your stepbrother died when he was young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
You had a busy house with the brothers that stayed with you and then you had a girl who stayed with you, the servant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh - oh, aye, we never - well Emmie was here during - well she came - she came 
- the spring I think - before my father - she was here when my father died. Emmie. She was quite a nice lassie that. Emmie came - in - well she was just a lassie but I say she used to come and get away home to play and come back and sleep. You know. Well 
she just lived - in -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Like your daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 You'd keep an eye on her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well she just lived in the house. Yes, and that - we just all lived together. Emmie -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Did she just do odd jobs about the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 Yes, wash the dishes a
nd - things. And help. And of course she could look after the baby. She could look after - Willie. I can remember that time when - when - this cousin come in and - oh I would - oh - oh she would insist that we go out, we never got out and we - well of cou
r
se you - you do things to please folks sometimes. Of course - if we - if we had wanted to go Effie could have looked after Willie. She knew him, yes, and - and - of course she was sitting there. And of course - this cousin would be wanting to - would - wo
u
ld think that she - she was a nursemaid you see, she think - and of course there were - your - your child'll sense there's something that - going on. Of course Willie took it - he was a good sleeper. But he took and he didna sleep. Oh, she told me the nex
t
 day. She says, Auntie - Auntie Hetty had to - she was - she was in an awful state. With Willie. She'd be wanting to - she'd slap him to make him lie down or something. I said, oh well, I said, there'll naebody get the chance to hit my bairn again as long
 as we're here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 After Effie left did you have anybody else to live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Well - after Effie left - more or less - I - I - I could aye get a auntie - and auntie or somebody to come and give mea a - if I wanted somebody. I kept in touch with Effie wh
en she left and got married, did I tell you about - I told you about - she had to get married, ultimately. She got into good places and - of course she went on and I don't know whether - I told you about - I think I did mention that her father came in - a
n
d - a lot - there were a lot of - at the end of the first world war lots of - young wives - like wives that had - their men had been away, were having babies. Now Willie come in the shop and he heard old Willis telling me something. He says, is that Emmie
 got a baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid556246 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 So after that you just had people in for the day to give you a hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6565549 WS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16322180\charrsid10313804 
Oh well I could - if I want - oh yes. If I wanted anybody - generally some of our aunties would come. Oh I think I would have an auntie - oh, for a good while, she 
used to come daily, like no - no every day but - about twice or thrice a week, I just didna - I didna mind but - I kept in touch with the family as long as - I needed to.
\par }}